1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:02,000
 Hvala, zbignac,stralnobankarski_div.

2
00:00:02,000 --> 00:00:28,680
 Hello, everyone, ladies and gentlemen. On behalf of Operation Industrial Bank, I would like to welcome all of you. I will give a few housekeeping remarks a little bit later on, but first I would like to give the floor to our governor and Mr. Boris Vujicic to have this welcome speech or introductory presentation, and I hope we will have enough chairs here during the fall.

3
00:00:28,680 --> 00:00:30,680
 Mr. Gavard.

4
00:00:30,680 --> 00:00:48,680
 Thank you, Lenarda, a warm welcome to all of you, to the Croatia National Bank, to the Forum on the Digital Euro and the Central Bank Digital Currents.

5
00:00:48,680 --> 00:00:57,360
 Let me extend the special welcome to Evelyn Vitlux, the Program Manager of the Euro Project at the European Central Bank,

6
00:00:57,360 --> 00:01:15,360
 to Tamara Perko, who is the President of the Croatian Banking Association, Darko Tipović, Old Friend from the University, who is the President of the Croatian Economic Association, and Takeshi Kito from Elevandi, Japan, who, I have been told, helped a lot also in the organization of this event.

7
00:01:15,360 --> 00:01:20,360
 This is a, this is a kind of, this is a kind of discussion on the project of the Digital Euro in Croatia.

8
00:01:20,360 --> 00:01:45,360
 It's not that we have not talked about it before, but with this forum, we kind of tried to launch the wider discussion on the, on the Digital Euro, because we think it is the timing now at this stage of the development of the project to have a broader, broader discussion.

9
00:01:45,360 --> 00:01:57,360
 And I'm happy to see that we'll have two excellent panels today that will discuss open issues, some which are, I would say, clear and uncontroversial.

10
00:01:57,360 --> 00:02:06,360
 And some which still ignite different opinions and, and the discussions.

11
00:02:06,360 --> 00:02:18,360
 It will be also a good opportunity for the media to ask the questions that they have on the, on the Euro and on the project of the Digital Euro.

12
00:02:18,360 --> 00:02:24,360
 Uh, and I will also say a few words, uh, later on, uh, for the, for the media.

13
00:02:24,360 --> 00:02:30,360
 Uh, the project is, is only one of the many projects, as you know, in worldwide.

14
00:02:30,360 --> 00:02:37,360
 There are approximately 100 jurisdictions around the world, which deliberate on the central bank digital currencies.

15
00:02:37,360 --> 00:02:42,360
 There were some who started early, uh, like our friends from Sweden.

16
00:02:42,360 --> 00:02:49,360
 Uh, there are some who stopped also, uh, after a few steps and, uh, are now a bit stalled.

17
00:02:49,360 --> 00:02:52,360
 There are some who have put the project on the back burner.

18
00:02:52,360 --> 00:03:01,360
 Uh, and there are some who have already implemented, uh, at least in the small areas, the, the concept of the central bank digital currencies.

19
00:03:01,360 --> 00:03:10,360
 You will hear from Evelyn, who is, uh, who is the right person to tell you where we are in the Europe, uh, with the development of, of this project.

20
00:03:10,360 --> 00:03:16,360
 And what are the, what are the main ideas that we had when we started to develop the project?

21
00:03:16,360 --> 00:03:27,360
 One of them is certainly that, uh, the, uh, central bank money, uh, public money is at the moment available only in the form of cash.

22
00:03:27,360 --> 00:03:38,360
 Uh, the, uh, the, uh, the private money bank, bank's money when the bank grant a loan and the money appears on your account.

23
00:03:38,360 --> 00:03:43,360
 That's all, that's all in a digital format, in the electronic format.

24
00:03:43,360 --> 00:03:56,360
 So now with, uh, uh, spread growth in the use of the digital money, we thought that the public should also get a public form of, uh, the central bank.

25
00:03:56,360 --> 00:03:58,360
 The central bank digital money.

26
00:03:58,360 --> 00:04:07,360
 And this is one thing that we aim to achieve with, uh, launching the, uh, European central bank digital currency.

27
00:04:07,360 --> 00:04:24,360
 The other is the, something that we call, uh, strategic autonomy, uh, primarily in the, in the area of the payment services to have an independent European platform for payment services independent of non-European.

28
00:04:24,360 --> 00:04:39,360
 uh, providers, uh, which, uh, which gives more resilience to the, to the payment system in Europe also helps in, in, in, uh, uh, technical aspects of cyber attacks at, uh, et cetera.

29
00:04:39,360 --> 00:04:47,360
 Uh, but of course there are many, uh, many, uh, issues, many questions around the central bank digital currency.

30
00:04:47,360 --> 00:04:50,360
 Not everything of course has been yet decided.

31
00:04:50,360 --> 00:04:53,360
 It's still, uh, project under development.

32
00:04:53,360 --> 00:05:07,360
 And I'm sure that, uh, uh, as we get the feedback from, uh, from you, from, of course, banks who are the very important partners in the, in the project, because they will have a major role in the, in the project.

33
00:05:07,360 --> 00:05:23,360
 We will be able to, to, to set the, the central bank digital currency, digital Europe in the best possible way and most useful way for the citizens, which is in the end of the, the, the, the end goal, which is very important.

34
00:05:23,360 --> 00:05:41,360
 Uh, there has been, uh, a lot of, uh, uh, I've heard, I've read at the, at the, at the internet forums worry whether the digital, uh, Euro will, uh, to some extent, infringe the privacy of the, of the citizens.

35
00:05:41,360 --> 00:05:46,360
 Uh, the, uh, conspiracy theories spread very, very quickly.

36
00:05:46,360 --> 00:05:58,360
 And, uh, we are there to assure no, the, the privacy is one of the most important things that, uh, we, uh, take care about in development of the, of the digital Europe.

37
00:05:58,360 --> 00:06:16,360
 And, uh, in the end, no, uh, having a digital Europe and having a central bank behind that might, in terms of the privacy be more private than having a private companies behind your, your transactions.

38
00:06:16,360 --> 00:06:23,360
 Uh, so I hope that the, the two panels was also answered these questions and worries that, that appear sometime.

39
00:06:23,360 --> 00:06:32,360
 Uh, and I wish you, uh, very nice discussions with panels and then, uh, a nice lunch.

40
00:06:32,360 --> 00:06:33,360
 Thank you very much.

41
00:06:33,360 --> 00:06:40,360
 Okay.

42
00:06:40,360 --> 00:06:41,360
 Uh, thank you governor.

43
00:06:41,360 --> 00:06:48,360
 So, uh, we will have, uh, two panels and there will be some time for each panel at the end of the panel for the questions.

44
00:06:48,360 --> 00:06:50,360
 I'll take care of the time.

45
00:06:50,360 --> 00:06:53,360
 So this is why I'm looking at, uh, our deputy and she will be moderator.

46
00:06:53,360 --> 00:06:55,360
 I'll take care that we have enough time for the questions.

47
00:06:55,360 --> 00:06:59,360
 And now there is the first, uh, panel is about the digital Europe.

48
00:06:59,360 --> 00:07:01,360
 Second one is about the CVDC.

49
00:07:01,360 --> 00:07:04,360
 So each panel will be preceded with the presentation.

50
00:07:04,360 --> 00:07:11,360
 And I would like to invite Ms. Evelyn Witlax, program manager of the European Central Bank on the digital Europe project.

51
00:07:11,360 --> 00:07:16,360
 She will give introductory, the introductory presentation to frame the discussion.

52
00:07:16,360 --> 00:07:19,360
 And then later on, we will have the discussion and questions.

53
00:07:19,360 --> 00:07:20,360
 So Ms. Witlax, please.

54
00:07:20,360 --> 00:07:25,360
 Well, thank you very much.

55
00:07:25,360 --> 00:07:45,360
 Uh, thank you for the invitation and thank you to the Croatian Central Bank for organizing, uh, this event because we find it very important to have an open discussion on the digital Euro because the digital Euro is something for everybody.

56
00:07:45,360 --> 00:07:52,360
 So it's good that we have, uh, an open discussion, uh, uh, in each, uh, Euro area, uh, country.

57
00:07:52,360 --> 00:07:59,360
 So, um, as Croatians, I think you are a special country because you only, uh, uh, joined the Euro one year ago.

58
00:07:59,360 --> 00:08:14,360
 Uh, and, uh, I hope that you have seen some benefits, uh, uh, of, uh, now being able to pay with the Euro amongst which, for example, that you can take your cash, uh, travel across the Euro countries and you can pay wherever you want.

59
00:08:14,360 --> 00:08:16,360
 And you don't need to exchange.

60
00:08:16,360 --> 00:08:21,360
 Actually, the digital Euro will provide something similar, but then an additional form.

61
00:08:21,360 --> 00:08:33,360
 It would allow you if you, uh, travel that you can just pay with the same payment means that you use here in Croatia, both in stores, but also, uh, online.

62
00:08:33,360 --> 00:08:43,360
 So, um, today I would like to talk you through a set, uh, sort of status of the digital Euro, uh, and, uh, talk you through all the thinking that we have.

63
00:08:43,360 --> 00:08:56,360
 But let's start at the beginning because why, uh, are, is the Euro system system together, as was said by the governor already considering, uh, a digital Euro.

64
00:08:56,360 --> 00:08:57,360
 And we're not the only central bank.

65
00:08:57,360 --> 00:09:05,360
 Actually, the majority of central banks are considering a central bank digital currency, which we call in our case, uh, digital Euro.

66
00:09:05,360 --> 00:09:09,360
 Uh, so in this presentation, I will take you along three main pillars.

67
00:09:09,360 --> 00:09:14,360
 So one, it's the natural, natural evolution of cash.

68
00:09:14,360 --> 00:09:19,360
 So it's the adaptation of the current form, uh, of, uh, central bank money that we have cash.

69
00:09:19,360 --> 00:09:24,360
 The other one is it will facilitate, uh, uh, the life of European citizens.

70
00:09:24,360 --> 00:09:28,360
 And last but not least, it will strengthen our, uh, strategic autonomy.

71
00:09:28,360 --> 00:09:32,360
 So let me take you through these three pillars.

72
00:09:32,360 --> 00:09:41,360
 Um, so the first one is, is that we see that even though, uh, the Euro system is extremely committed to cash and stays committed to cash.

73
00:09:41,360 --> 00:09:44,360
 Uh, as a colleague of mine said, cash is our baby.

74
00:09:44,360 --> 00:09:45,360
 So we love it.

75
00:09:45,360 --> 00:09:51,360
 Uh, but what we see is that, uh, the people use it less for doing retail payments.

76
00:09:51,360 --> 00:09:54,360
 So there's a change going, uh, ongoing.

77
00:09:54,360 --> 00:10:04,360
 We saw, for example, that between 2019 and 2022, uh, the share of, uh, uh, cash payments declined from 72 to 59.

78
00:10:04,360 --> 00:10:08,360
 So that's really quite a steep, uh, decline in only three years time.

79
00:10:08,360 --> 00:10:11,360
 I'm coming from the Netherlands.

80
00:10:11,360 --> 00:10:16,360
 Uh, we have Alexi here coming from Finland, uh, where we have, uh, very different figures.

81
00:10:16,360 --> 00:10:21,360
 For example, in the Netherlands, only one in five transactions is still done, uh, with cash.

82
00:10:21,360 --> 00:10:26,360
 So we, we see a trend that the citizens would like to pay more digitally.

83
00:10:26,360 --> 00:10:34,360
 So we believe that therefore, uh, providing the benefits of, uh, cash, which is central bank money.

84
00:10:34,360 --> 00:10:35,360
 Um, but it does make a difference.

85
00:10:35,360 --> 00:10:36,360
 We do see this.

86
00:10:36,360 --> 00:10:52,360
 Of course, if people feel insecure, they go to cash because they think it's, uh, it's, uh, it's, uh, it's, it's their, really their money.

87
00:10:52,360 --> 00:10:58,360
 Um, so, um, the digital euro would be a form of cash, but then put digitally.

88
00:10:58,360 --> 00:11:03,360
 So, um, we will look to a couple of the most, uh, liked features of cash.

89
00:11:03,360 --> 00:11:07,360
 For example, uh, the fact that you can use it everywhere.

90
00:11:07,360 --> 00:11:10,360
 Uh, uh, the fact that it's, uh, highly private.

91
00:11:10,360 --> 00:11:15,360
 Uh, so these things we really try to incorporate in the design of the digital euro going forward.

92
00:11:15,360 --> 00:11:18,360
 I will come back on both of these topics later on.

93
00:11:18,360 --> 00:11:24,360
 Then next to that, it will make people life easier throughout the euro area.

94
00:11:24,360 --> 00:11:36,360
 Um, because we have gotten used to it, uh, that if you travel or if you travel online, uh, that you need to, uh, you, there's not one way to pay with euro.

95
00:11:36,360 --> 00:11:45,360
 Uh, so for example, uh, in Germany, if you pay online, it's actually most, uh, mostly PayPal, uh, the only, uh, opportunity that is there.

96
00:11:45,360 --> 00:11:47,360
 If you go to the Netherlands is ideal.

97
00:11:47,360 --> 00:11:49,360
 If you go to Spain, it's be zoom.

98
00:11:49,360 --> 00:11:52,360
 Um, but it, there's not one way.

99
00:11:52,360 --> 00:11:58,360
 If you also, for example, want to share, uh, a bill amongst, uh, I work in now in the ECB.

100
00:11:58,360 --> 00:12:04,360
 So I have like a colleague from all over Europe, we can not digitally share the bill.

101
00:12:04,360 --> 00:12:06,360
 Uh, we need to pay with cash.

102
00:12:06,360 --> 00:12:14,360
 So there's really still a lot of use cases where we cannot have one single way to pay with a euro digitally.

103
00:12:14,360 --> 00:12:17,360
 So with the digital euro, this would be possible.

104
00:12:17,360 --> 00:12:21,360
 Um, and let me stress again, it will not replace anything.

105
00:12:21,360 --> 00:12:26,360
 So it will not replace cash and it will not replace the current private means of payments.

106
00:12:26,360 --> 00:12:33,360
 It will be an additional choice that people can use if they want, and they can't, they don't need to use if they don't want.

107
00:12:33,360 --> 00:12:41,360
 If we look to the current draft legislation, which is currently at the table, we see also that the digital euro will be granted legal tender.

108
00:12:41,360 --> 00:12:43,360
 And what does it mean practically?

109
00:12:43,360 --> 00:12:53,360
 It means that if you go to your bank, your bank will be able and will need to provide you with digital euro, uh, accounts and a means of payments.

110
00:12:53,360 --> 00:13:00,360
 While on the other hand, merchants that now currently accept digital payments will need to accept the digital euro.

111
00:13:00,360 --> 00:13:02,360
 So with that, you can really trust.

112
00:13:02,360 --> 00:13:07,360
 If you have a digital euro, you can travel across Europe and pay wherever you want.

113
00:13:07,360 --> 00:13:14,360
 And last but not least, it will tackle some of the geopolitical challenges and, uh, strengthen our resilience.

114
00:13:14,360 --> 00:13:21,360
 So if we look to the current retail payment landscape in Europe, also not something that people normally think about because you just think.

115
00:13:21,360 --> 00:13:22,360
 It works.

116
00:13:22,360 --> 00:13:24,360
 I, I need to pay and it works.

117
00:13:24,360 --> 00:13:26,360
 You trust actually that it works.

118
00:13:26,360 --> 00:13:33,360
 Uh, but roughly 70% of our transactions are done over non-European payment rails.

119
00:13:33,360 --> 00:13:42,360
 And I think for something so essential as payments, uh, which is like water and gas and electricity, you just trust it's there.

120
00:13:42,360 --> 00:13:45,360
 Um, uh, that should also be the case for, for payments.

121
00:13:45,360 --> 00:13:56,360
 And this high dependency on non-European payment, uh, providers, uh, should be a concern of us and would, is, would be something that the digital euro would address.

122
00:13:56,360 --> 00:14:05,360
 Um, and on, on, on, on the, on the flip side of that, the digital euro would provide a platform, uh, for innovation.

123
00:14:05,360 --> 00:14:11,360
 As I've just described, the digital euro would be widely accepted, uh, and widely used.

124
00:14:11,360 --> 00:14:20,360
 So, uh, actually every citizen in the euro area would be able to pay with the digital euro if they want, and every merchant, uh, will be able to accept it.

125
00:14:20,360 --> 00:14:29,360
 Uh, so that also means that if you would want to do innovation on top of payment rails, uh, for example, uh, like conditional payments or stuff.

126
00:14:29,360 --> 00:14:34,360
 You can build on this rails and you have a reach almost immediately over the whole of Europe.

127
00:14:34,360 --> 00:14:39,360
 Uh, and, uh, last but not least payments has a tendency.

128
00:14:39,360 --> 00:14:41,360
 It is a network product.

129
00:14:41,360 --> 00:14:48,360
 Uh, so it has a tendency of dominance, um, uh, and with the digital euro with, which is a public good.

130
00:14:48,360 --> 00:15:00,360
 We will make sure that there stays sufficient competition in the market so that we also make sure that the payment system, uh, remains, uh, uh, effective, uh, and efficient.

131
00:15:02,360 --> 00:15:07,360
 So I'm not going to talk you through everything here, but, uh, and let me, uh, tell you what is the gist of this.

132
00:15:07,360 --> 00:15:15,360
 So the, the digital euro, uh, we now talk as is it, we, we, one thing, but it will look a bit, uh, uh, different.

133
00:15:15,360 --> 00:15:22,360
 So we will design it for three use cases so that you can pay, as I said already earlier, pair person to person.

134
00:15:22,360 --> 00:15:27,360
 So I can, uh, uh, pay back for, uh, I dunno, a restaurant bill.

135
00:15:27,360 --> 00:15:31,360
 If we want to share, for example, it will be available for point of sale.

136
00:15:31,360 --> 00:15:34,360
 So in store payments and for e-commerce payments.

137
00:15:34,360 --> 00:15:39,360
 So these are the three use cases for which the digital euro in its first instance would be designed.

138
00:15:39,360 --> 00:15:44,360
 Then, uh, an important one as well is, is that there will be two types of digital euro.

139
00:15:44,360 --> 00:15:46,360
 One would be the online one.

140
00:15:46,360 --> 00:15:54,360
 Uh, which might look a bit like, uh, a payment methods that you currently know, but there will also be an offline variant.

141
00:15:54,360 --> 00:16:01,360
 And the offline variant would mean that you can pay, even if there's no internet connection, even if there's no electricity.

142
00:16:01,360 --> 00:16:12,360
 Uh, but it also provides a very high level of privacy because actually what happens is that there will be two secure elements, which is the chip, for example, in your mobile phone.

143
00:16:12,360 --> 00:16:16,360
 Or a specific card on which you can store digital euros.

144
00:16:16,360 --> 00:16:20,360
 And that would be as if you get like 50 euros out of the ATM.

145
00:16:20,360 --> 00:16:24,360
 Uh, you put it in your pocket, but then you put it on the secure element.

146
00:16:24,360 --> 00:16:29,360
 And then if you want to do a payment, you can hold these two devices close to each other.

147
00:16:29,360 --> 00:16:31,360
 And then the payment has been done.

148
00:16:31,360 --> 00:16:40,360
 So it means that unlike with an online transaction, it always need to travel over a network to it, to get to the other, the bank of the one that you want to pay.

149
00:16:40,360 --> 00:16:45,360
 But with an offline payment, it's really a transaction between two devices.

150
00:16:45,360 --> 00:16:47,360
 So it's very, very private.

151
00:16:47,360 --> 00:16:50,360
 Um, on the consumer device, I've said it a lot.

152
00:16:50,360 --> 00:16:55,360
 So mobile phone will be one, uh, but we also foresee, uh, a physical card.

153
00:16:55,360 --> 00:17:00,360
 And of course, if it can be on the mobile phone, it also will be provided with a web interface.

154
00:17:00,360 --> 00:17:05,360
 Um, then, uh, on the right hand side, you see the technology.

155
00:17:05,360 --> 00:17:14,360
 So it could be, uh, alias space could be NFC, which is, uh, a contactless payment as we do it in the shop, uh, or with QR codes.

156
00:17:14,360 --> 00:17:20,360
 And then last but not least, the way that you could have access to is, is actually twofold.

157
00:17:20,360 --> 00:17:31,360
 So if you have it on your mobile phone, you can easily, uh, either use, uh, this via, uh, the internet banking environment that your bank, uh, provides.

158
00:17:31,360 --> 00:17:52,360
 Of course, this is dependent if the bank would offer this, uh, but next to that, there is also the digital euro app, uh, which would be there for the people that would like to use something, uh, separately or, uh, can also be reused for PSPs that are too small to invest themselves in building these mobile apps.

159
00:17:52,360 --> 00:17:56,360
 Uh, privacy and data, uh, protection.

160
00:17:56,360 --> 00:18:00,360
 Uh, this is a very important, uh, point as was also pointed out by the governor.

161
00:18:00,360 --> 00:18:04,360
 Uh, and we also got this back from the public consultation.

162
00:18:04,360 --> 00:18:09,360
 We did before we went into the investigation phase that, uh, privacy is very important.

163
00:18:09,360 --> 00:18:13,360
 So let me, uh, tell you a couple of things.

164
00:18:13,360 --> 00:18:19,360
 So, um, with the, uh, privacy, we look to a couple of elements.

165
00:18:19,360 --> 00:18:23,360
 So one is the end to end, uh, privacy that would be there.

166
00:18:23,360 --> 00:18:31,360
 Um, so that starts from, from you doing a payment still, uh, receiving the payment for the online.

167
00:18:31,360 --> 00:18:43,360
 The current draft legislation says that the banks need to have access as they have today to your data in order to do AML and CFD, uh, uh, uh, checks.

168
00:18:43,360 --> 00:18:50,360
 Um, for offline, as I already explained a bit earlier, this is differently because those transaction will not go to the bank.

169
00:18:50,360 --> 00:18:55,360
 They will not go to the bank and they will not go to the, uh, uh, to the European central bank.

170
00:18:55,360 --> 00:18:59,360
 It would be like withdrawing cash from the ATM.

171
00:18:59,360 --> 00:19:03,360
 So the bank would know that you withdraw 50 euros for offline transactions.

172
00:19:03,360 --> 00:19:16,360
 And at a certain point in time, if you want to put something from your offline holdings on, uh, on your account again, then we would know that you have put 50 euros back on your account, but all the transaction in between will stay private.

173
00:19:16,360 --> 00:19:22,360
 Then for the online one, then apart from the banks, there is the part of the Euro system.

174
00:19:22,360 --> 00:19:25,360
 And there's a lot of concerns, uh, or a lot of concerns.

175
00:19:25,360 --> 00:19:31,360
 There are people that are concerned about that, about the information that the Euro system would have.

176
00:19:31,360 --> 00:19:40,360
 But let me reassure you the way that we, uh, build the system would be that we cannot connect any transaction to a private individual.

177
00:19:40,360 --> 00:19:51,360
 And that's much more private than any current private payment means that is there because currently your payment data flows from, from one system to the other without being anonymized.

178
00:19:51,360 --> 00:19:55,360
 But for, uh, for the digital Euro, it would be like this.

179
00:19:55,360 --> 00:20:00,360
 So we would be settling transactions without knowing for whom we do these transactions.

180
00:20:00,360 --> 00:20:06,360
 Of course, we will be compliant with EU regulations and also with the data protection law.

181
00:20:06,360 --> 00:20:09,360
 So there is nothing, uh, uh, there.

182
00:20:09,360 --> 00:20:15,360
 So another important element of the digital Euro is financial inclusion.

183
00:20:15,360 --> 00:20:23,360
 And that is a financial digital inclusion because we, uh, have still people that don't have access to bank accounts.

184
00:20:23,360 --> 00:20:34,360
 But I think we have increasingly more people that find it difficult to follow, uh, uh, uh, the digital developments and feel confident that, that they can pay there.

185
00:20:34,360 --> 00:20:41,360
 So we have really in the design built in features to make it as inclusive and accessible as possible.

186
00:20:41,360 --> 00:20:49,360
 And we're very happy that quite a number of these, uh, uh, points that we have made are also in the draft legislation, which is currently under discussion.

187
00:20:49,360 --> 00:21:07,360
 Um, so one important element for the consumer organization in this point was that there would also be a physical card, uh, because people, there are people that find digitalization difficult, find a card easier to handle, uh, than a mobile phone.

188
00:21:07,360 --> 00:21:14,360
 Um, but more importantly, because we actually want to make people to, to feel confident, comfortable in the digital world as well.

189
00:21:14,360 --> 00:21:27,360
 Uh, there would be, uh, uh, uh, the possibility for users to have, uh, access to face to face technical, uh, support, um, and also to easily switch from intermediaries.

190
00:21:27,360 --> 00:21:34,360
 Currently, if you need to close an account and move, uh, to another account, that is quite a hassle, but in the design of the digital Euro,

191
00:21:34,360 --> 00:21:41,360
 it will be very easy to switch your account from one provider to the other without losing any of your history.

192
00:21:41,360 --> 00:21:47,360
 And it means like, if you now move from one bank to the other, you'll get a new, uh, account number for the digital Euro.

193
00:21:47,360 --> 00:21:53,360
 We will always keep your digital Euro account number, uh, making this very easy.

194
00:21:53,360 --> 00:21:58,360
 Um, also offline, uh, is very important, of course, for financial inclusion.

195
00:21:58,360 --> 00:22:06,360
 Uh, and the last point is that indeed the draft legislation said there should be public entities that provide this face to face, uh, support.

196
00:22:06,360 --> 00:22:09,360
 So that could be different per country, how this is set up.

197
00:22:09,360 --> 00:22:28,360
 Uh, so as was mentioned also by the governor, uh, the intermediaries, the PSPs, uh, the banks, uh, financial institutions play a key role, uh, in, in the ecosystem because they will be the distributors of the digital Euro, uh, towards the end users.

198
00:22:28,360 --> 00:22:31,360
 And the end users being consumers and merchants.

199
00:22:31,360 --> 00:22:39,360
 Uh, so we really, uh, want to keep the current way of working so that we don't disintermediate, uh,

200
00:22:39,360 --> 00:22:41,360
 the PSPs, they keep the primary relationship.

201
00:22:41,360 --> 00:22:45,360
 So, um, a couple of things that are on this slide.

202
00:22:45,360 --> 00:22:53,360
 So on the left hand side, you see a couple of these things that we find it important to, to, uh, to keep, uh, the current balance.

203
00:22:53,360 --> 00:22:57,360
 So the digital Euro just distribution will be done, uh, via PSPs.

204
00:22:57,360 --> 00:23:08,360
 They will have the customer relation, uh, and, um, we are for the digital Euro developing standards to make sure that you can pay everywhere in the Euro area.

205
00:23:08,360 --> 00:23:12,360
 These standards could also be reused for European payment solutions.

206
00:23:12,360 --> 00:23:18,360
 Uh, and with that, actually, we hope to unlock even further the potential of instant payments.

207
00:23:18,360 --> 00:23:28,360
 Then, uh, uh, from some, uh, payment service providers, they are concerned about the impact on liquidity because like cash, the cash is your money.

208
00:23:28,360 --> 00:23:33,360
 So it's not on the balance of the bank and for digital Euro, it would be the same.

209
00:23:33,360 --> 00:23:39,360
 It would be, uh, uh, on, on our balance sheet and in your pockets, uh, uh, to say so.

210
00:23:39,360 --> 00:23:49,360
 So for that, in order to make sure that this, the, the financial system is not destabilized, there are a couple of elements in the, uh, design that should ensure this.

211
00:23:49,360 --> 00:23:54,360
 That's one is the holding limits for end users, uh, a waterfall functionality.

212
00:23:54,360 --> 00:23:55,360
 What does it mean?

213
00:23:55,360 --> 00:24:11,360
 It, it means that if, if there's a holding limit of say 3000, um, and you want to do a transactional 3,00 and five year old, um, you could still do it because you would top up your account.

214
00:24:11,360 --> 00:24:20,360
 And then you would pay, it would also allow you to hold like lower amounts, uh, uh, on, on your digital Euro account because you can trust that you can always pay.

215
00:24:20,360 --> 00:24:29,360
 So if you have always 100 euros or 200 euros and by coincidence, you need to do a big, uh, a small, uh, bigger payment, this can be done seamlessly.

216
00:24:29,360 --> 00:24:37,360
 Uh, and last but not least, uh, uh, uh, the, the, your system has said that they will not renumerate, uh, the digital Euro.

217
00:24:37,360 --> 00:24:46,360
 So to make it very much like cash, this point I briefly touched upon, uh, and this is the, the payment rails.

218
00:24:46,360 --> 00:24:53,360
 As I said, uh, before currently roughly 70% of our transactions are running over non-European payment rails.

219
00:24:53,360 --> 00:24:59,360
 Uh, and we find it important that we have more transactions over European owned payment rails.

220
00:24:59,360 --> 00:25:06,360
 Uh, so we will, uh, uh, implement those when we implement the digital Euro.

221
00:25:06,360 --> 00:25:13,360
 But those rails can also be reused for private solutions, uh, uh, uh, European solutions.

222
00:25:13,360 --> 00:25:18,360
 And for that, they could much easier scale and roll out, uh, than they currently can.

223
00:25:18,360 --> 00:25:25,360
 And with that, we can really reduce the dependence on other Europe, non-European players.

224
00:25:25,360 --> 00:25:29,360
 For that, we are working on, uh, on a scheme.

225
00:25:29,360 --> 00:25:33,360
 We do that in a rule book, uh, in a rule book development group.

226
00:25:33,360 --> 00:25:36,360
 And the rule book development group consists of all the stakeholders actually.

227
00:25:36,360 --> 00:25:38,360
 So merchants are represented there.

228
00:25:38,360 --> 00:25:39,360
 Consumers are represented there.

229
00:25:39,360 --> 00:25:44,360
 And the financial institutions being banks or non-bank financial institutions.

230
00:25:44,360 --> 00:25:56,360
 Um, and we need that in order to ensure that whatever your bank gives you like a card or QR code, that, uh, wherever you travel in the Euro area, each merchant can, uh, accept this.

231
00:25:56,360 --> 00:25:59,360
 And for that, you need to define these standards.

232
00:25:59,360 --> 00:26:05,360
 Uh, so it will establish common standards to ensure this pan-European reach and a harmonized payment experience.

233
00:26:05,360 --> 00:26:08,360
 So not that every time you pay is completely different.

234
00:26:08,360 --> 00:26:15,360
 Um, on top of that, it will provide this platform for all which they can and market players can further innovate.

235
00:26:15,360 --> 00:26:24,360
 Uh, and as I said before, it allows domestic, uh, uh, uh, players to, uh, to widen their scope.

236
00:26:24,360 --> 00:26:31,360
 Um, so let me then come to a bit of the end of what I wanted to say.

237
00:26:31,360 --> 00:26:34,360
 So we have been working on the investigation phase.

238
00:26:34,360 --> 00:26:38,360
 That was work we have done between 2021 and October last year.

239
00:26:38,360 --> 00:26:45,360
 Uh, and there we have worked mainly on, uh, the design proposal as well on the technical explorations.

240
00:26:45,360 --> 00:26:52,360
 We currently are in the preparation phase, which started in November and will last to, uh, at the end of 2025.

241
00:26:52,360 --> 00:26:55,360
 There are four main deliverables that we would have.

242
00:26:55,360 --> 00:26:59,360
 So the first one is, uh, to finalize this Rebook.

243
00:26:59,360 --> 00:27:00,360
 Why is this important?

244
00:27:00,360 --> 00:27:08,360
 Because it would make sure that the moment a decision is taken, uh, to issue digital Euro, everybody would know what to implement.

245
00:27:08,360 --> 00:27:10,360
 Um, so that is important.

246
00:27:10,360 --> 00:27:16,360
 Uh, the other one is, uh, selecting the service providers for the parts that the Euro system needs to provide.

247
00:27:16,360 --> 00:27:27,360
 So for example, the settlement engine, um, we want to further learn through experimentation, not only on a techno, a technological basis, but also on a user experience.

248
00:27:27,360 --> 00:27:33,360
 And last but not least, we will do further deep dives and also prepare a plan.

249
00:27:33,360 --> 00:27:40,360
 Uh, might a decision be taken, uh, to, uh, to go ahead with the digital Euro so that we have a plan to implement.

250
00:27:40,360 --> 00:27:44,360
 And then at the end of 2025, we will go back to the governing council.

251
00:27:44,360 --> 00:27:48,360
 And then, uh, um, we need to see where we are.

252
00:27:48,360 --> 00:27:51,360
 So important is of course, the findings of the preparation phase.

253
00:27:51,360 --> 00:28:05,360
 But what is also important to know is, is that in parallel with us working in the preparation phase, uh, the co-legislators currently are discussing the draft legislation that, which was published by the commission last year, June.

254
00:28:05,360 --> 00:28:12,360
 Uh, so we will also there, or we are there providing technical support where asked and where needed.

255
00:28:12,360 --> 00:28:26,360
 Um, and we have of course committed ourselves that we will always make sure that, uh, uh, the digital Euro will stay in line with, uh, the design that will be approved by, uh, the co-legislators.

256
00:28:26,360 --> 00:28:29,360
 So with that, I would like to come to a close.

257
00:28:29,360 --> 00:28:30,360
 Thank you very much.

258
00:28:30,360 --> 00:28:31,360
 And looking forward to the panel.

259
00:28:31,360 --> 00:28:32,360
 Thank you.

260
00:28:32,360 --> 00:28:32,360
 Thank you.

261
00:28:32,360 --> 00:28:33,360
 Thank you, Evelyn.

