00:36:00,360 --> 00:36:02,360
 Thank you very much for the invitation.

347
00:36:02,360 --> 00:36:04,360
 Um, my personal role.

348
00:36:04,360 --> 00:36:07,360
 I've been in payments for 26 years.

349
00:36:07,360 --> 00:36:14,360
 So maybe a little bit longer than Evelyn has been, but, uh, still, uh, we have done in this time.

350
00:36:14,360 --> 00:36:18,360
 Uh, we have joined the Euro area, SEP and so on.

351
00:36:18,360 --> 00:36:25,360
 Currently I'm responsible for operations, uh, oversight, supervision, and strategic development.

352
00:36:25,360 --> 00:36:29,360
 And, uh, as concerns visit digital era itself.

353
00:36:29,360 --> 00:36:38,360
 Uh, we have been following, uh, stable kinds, uh, Facebook initiatives and so on now for almost, uh, eight, nine years.

354
00:36:38,360 --> 00:36:46,360
 And, uh, for me, everything has really started with the ECB report from October, 2020.

355
00:36:46,360 --> 00:36:59,360
 and from then on, when the high level task force at the ECB has been established, it was always our goal to be active participants in that, uh, high level task force.

356
00:36:59,360 --> 00:37:08,360
 And I have to tell that this is one of the goals, strategic goals of the Bank of Slovenia to be active on the project.

357
00:37:08,360 --> 00:37:17,360
 So, uh, we are somehow supporting our member of the high level task force to have our own opinions at the high level task force.

358
00:37:17,360 --> 00:37:30,360
 But I have to be clear, as you have stressed, uh, countries of the Euro area are very different, but we may argue among ourselves, but we should speak one language to the public.

359
00:37:30,360 --> 00:37:39,360
 And this is very important because it is the digital Euro which will be addressed to all the population of the Euro area.

360
00:37:39,360 --> 00:37:44,360
 So, there are only 350 million people which do not have the same background.

361
00:37:44,360 --> 00:37:50,360
 For example, to be very short, in Slovenia, financial inclusion is 99%.

362
00:37:50,360 --> 00:37:58,360
 Only 1% of people above 15 years does not have a bank account.

363
00:37:58,360 --> 00:38:00,360
 People do not want, they do not need.

364
00:38:00,360 --> 00:38:04,360
 It's not a matter of financial inclusion for Slovenia.

365
00:38:04,360 --> 00:38:06,360
 For some countries, it may be.

366
00:38:06,360 --> 00:38:16,360
 But on the other side, only 60% of people are using their smart devices to access their mobile bank or, uh, e-banking solutions.

367
00:38:16,360 --> 00:38:26,360
 So, even older people have smartphones, but what they do use them for YouTube and such things, not for financial services.

368
00:38:26,360 --> 00:38:35,360
 So, we see, uh, that a lot of communication will have to be done and Slovenians are really cash lovers.

369
00:38:35,360 --> 00:38:39,360
 We are the second country from the bottom.

370
00:38:39,360 --> 00:38:45,360
 Just, uh, Malta is ahead of us, uh, as concerns the use of cash.

371
00:38:45,360 --> 00:38:51,360
 More than 70% of payments in volume is made by cash.

372
00:38:51,360 --> 00:39:02,360
 So, this is surprising somehow because, uh, people have smart devices, smartphones, but still, there is something in cash that people still like.

373
00:39:02,360 --> 00:39:04,360
 So, this is the challenge.

374
00:39:04,360 --> 00:39:12,360
 And, uh, I believe that the digital euro should address all the population of the euro area the same way.

375
00:39:12,360 --> 00:39:18,360
 But national authorities should then communicate in a specific way within the national boundaries.

376
00:39:18,360 --> 00:39:26,360
 Uh, can you pinpoint what is it about the cash that, uh, our neighbors from Slovenia love that much?

377
00:39:26,360 --> 00:39:30,360
 Is it the privacy or some other aspect?

378
00:39:30,360 --> 00:39:32,360
 It is difficult to say.

379
00:39:32,360 --> 00:39:46,360
 I should not, uh, refer to the shadow economy, which is also an important, uh, role of cash, uh, because it is used for a shadow economy to avoid paying taxes and so on.

380
00:39:46,360 --> 00:39:50,360
 But people are just used to, I cannot, uh, go for it.

381
00:39:50,360 --> 00:39:55,360
 Uh, the ECB has performed, uh, a survey on the payment habits.

382
00:39:55,360 --> 00:40:05,360
 And, uh, the results of this, uh, survey are that, uh, especially people, uh, older than 65, they are very attached to cash.

383
00:40:05,360 --> 00:40:12,360
 While the youngsters, they use cash only when other possibilities are not available.

384
00:40:12,360 --> 00:40:23,360
 And it's quite often, it happens to me, uh, that I go to the restaurant and it's not possible to care, to pay with a cashless, uh, means of payment.

385
00:40:23,360 --> 00:40:32,360
 But the restaurant keeper, the owner, she or she exactly knows where the closest ATM is.

386
00:40:32,360 --> 00:40:37,360
 And I have to pay then 12 euros, uh, for visa withdrawal with a credit card.

387
00:40:37,360 --> 00:40:39,360
 And that's annoying for me.

388
00:40:39,360 --> 00:40:46,360
 That's annoying because I prefer carrying only my smartphone with me and paying at the moment with Apple Pay.

389
00:40:46,360 --> 00:40:49,360
 in the future, of course, with digital Europe.

390
00:40:49,360 --> 00:40:51,360
 Thank you very much.

391
00:40:51,360 --> 00:40:54,360
 Uh, now the question for Mr.

392
00:40:54,360 --> 00:40:59,360
 Mr. Green, uh, head of FinTech, uh, from, uh, the Central Bank of Finland.

393
00:40:59,360 --> 00:41:07,360
 So your country is somewhere on the opposite side when it comes to cash payments, uh, than, than Slovenia.

394
00:41:07,360 --> 00:41:13,360
 So, uh, first of all, how, uh, are you personally involved in digital Europe project?

395
00:41:13,360 --> 00:41:20,360
 And, uh, what are the sentiments, uh, in Finland towards the project?

396
00:41:20,360 --> 00:41:21,360
 Yes.

397
00:41:21,360 --> 00:41:22,360
 Thank you for the question.

398
00:41:22,360 --> 00:41:24,360
 And it's a pleasure to be part of this panel.

399
00:41:24,360 --> 00:41:31,360
 Um, so we started looking into this topic, I would say about eight years ago, 2015, 2016.

400
00:41:31,360 --> 00:41:39,360
 And that's when we set up a new function in the, in the central bank, um, which is the division that I'm heading now.

401
00:41:39,360 --> 00:41:41,360
 And it's within the payments department.

402
00:41:41,360 --> 00:41:46,360
 So in the payments department, we have our payment systems and oversight, and then we also have cash.

403
00:41:46,360 --> 00:41:49,360
 Uh, we kind of set up FinTech in between those.

404
00:41:49,360 --> 00:41:55,360
 So it both looks at the development of payment systems, but also the future of money itself.

405
00:41:55,360 --> 00:41:57,360
 So that's a very interesting position.

406
00:41:57,360 --> 00:42:00,360
 And we've had this function now for about eight years.

407
00:42:00,360 --> 00:42:06,360
 Um, so we've been involved in CBDC and digital Europe discussions from the very beginning.

408
00:42:06,360 --> 00:42:14,360
 As soon as they started, we, we, we, we got involved in those discussions and were part of the different, um, work streams of that particular project.

409
00:42:14,360 --> 00:42:17,360
 I myself am on the project steering group.

410
00:42:17,360 --> 00:42:26,360
 And then we have a team that's supporting myself and our, um, uh, high level task force members and other, other members who are on the, on that team.

411
00:42:26,360 --> 00:42:27,360
 And it's true.

412
00:42:27,360 --> 00:42:30,360
 Finland is maybe an example of a very highly digitized economy.

413
00:42:30,360 --> 00:42:36,360
 If not possibly depending on metric, maybe the, the most digitized in the Euro system in some sense.

414
00:42:36,360 --> 00:42:43,360
 So just to give context, we have the latest figures we have is about 7% of the population use cash.

415
00:42:43,360 --> 00:42:51,360
 So the rest about 90, 95% depend on, on card payments, but, but also digital payments in general.

416
00:42:51,360 --> 00:42:57,360
 And basically everything in our societies is digitized healthcare, travel, public services, everything.

417
00:42:57,360 --> 00:43:04,360
 And we have a very advanced, um, identification system, which was kind of underpins that.

418
00:43:04,360 --> 00:43:10,360
 So it's, uh, possible to do very reliable identification of, of people.

419
00:43:10,360 --> 00:43:14,360
 Um, that's very, really a necessity for, for all these digital services.

420
00:43:14,360 --> 00:43:22,360
 But I think the good news is that even our country, our central bank and our citizens love cash.

421
00:43:22,360 --> 00:43:26,360
 Even, even though we, we don't use it much, we don't want to get rid of it.

422
00:43:26,360 --> 00:43:33,360
 So if about 10 years ago, it looked like the trend was emerging that cash is declining.

423
00:43:33,360 --> 00:43:39,360
 Um, and some people made the extrapolation that, okay, maybe it will disappear entirely, but that's not actually what we're seeing.

424
00:43:39,360 --> 00:43:43,360
 So it did decline, but it's now kind of stable at a very low level.

425
00:43:43,360 --> 00:43:47,360
 And the last couple of polls that we've done, it's not really changing much.

426
00:43:47,360 --> 00:43:51,360
 So there's a, there's sort of small hardcore user group that still uses cash.

427
00:43:51,360 --> 00:43:55,360
 And a lot of people want to have that option available also in the future.

428
00:43:55,360 --> 00:44:07,360
 Um, so you can digitize the economy and you can digitize financial services to a very, very large extent, but there are some fundamentals that always have to be there.

429
00:44:07,360 --> 00:44:10,360
 And that's at least my view and one is cash.

430
00:44:10,360 --> 00:44:13,360
 The other is voting, but let's not talk about that today.

431
00:44:13,360 --> 00:44:14,360
 Okay.

432
00:44:14,360 --> 00:44:15,360
 Great.

433
00:44:15,360 --> 00:44:16,360
 Thank you.

434
00:44:16,360 --> 00:44:17,360
 Thank you.

435
00:44:17,360 --> 00:44:37,360
 Well, now we have heard the central bankers and, uh, uh, uh, far as we, we, we can, uh, understand, uh, the central bankers not only work on the digital Euro project, they, uh, support it wholeheartedly irrespective of, uh, the countries they come from.

436
00:44:37,360 --> 00:44:43,360
 And what about, uh, the bankers, the commercial bankers, you represent, uh, them here.

437
00:44:43,360 --> 00:44:51,360
 So, uh, have they already put a digital Euro project on their radars or is it still too far away?

438
00:44:51,360 --> 00:44:58,360
 And what are the sentiments of, uh, the, the bankers in Croatia towards digital Euro?

439
00:44:58,360 --> 00:45:03,360
 Uh, thank you very much for the invitation on the panel.

440
00:45:03,360 --> 00:45:10,360
 I'm the only one with exclusion of Mrs. Varese, uh, that is not from a central bank.

441
00:45:10,360 --> 00:45:23,360
 And, uh, I have a different opinion and feelings about, uh, digital Euro, uh, with regards to digital Euro on the European level, it's already on the radar for a long time.

442
00:45:23,360 --> 00:45:32,360
 So I'm also a member of the executive committee of European Banking Federation, and we are discussing their digital Euro a lot.

443
00:45:32,360 --> 00:45:40,360
 Uh, on the Croatian level, uh, we started to discuss, uh, the topic of the digital Euro.

444
00:45:40,360 --> 00:45:53,360
 We formed a working group within the Croatian Banking Association, uh, that's already, that started with its work and we started to learn about the digital Euro.

445
00:45:53,360 --> 00:46:00,360
 And I have to admit that, uh, uh, here we have a support of Croatian National Bank and thank you for that.

446
00:46:00,360 --> 00:46:06,360
 We already had an education, uh, for a commercial bank, uh, in organization of Croatian Central Bank.

447
00:46:06,360 --> 00:46:12,360
 And I think that this is a good way how to, how to introduce something new on the market.

448
00:46:12,360 --> 00:46:29,360
 I think that we need to discuss and, uh, we need to listen to each other because I see that on the European level within the European Banking Federation, there are a lot of hesitations with regard to digital Euro project.

449
00:46:29,360 --> 00:46:39,360
 Uh, a lot of open questions, uh, I don't have a feeling that, uh, there have been a lot of discussion on the European level.

450
00:46:39,360 --> 00:47:02,360
 Uh, because I see that the commercial banks are still very hesitant about, uh, Euro to put it mildly, not happy about the digital Euro, uh, with a lot of objections, with a lot of very worrying scenario analysis, what digital Euro will bring to commercial banking sectors.

451
00:47:02,360 --> 00:47:15,360
 So I think that there is a need really to discuss more and to be transparent and to try to solve the issues, uh, when the project is in the early phase.

452
00:47:15,360 --> 00:47:27,360
 What we have discussed on the European Banking Federation level is that we are fearing the scenario where, uh, this will go, uh, very far.

453
00:47:27,360 --> 00:47:36,360
 And that at a certain point, uh, the people will say, well, we already invested a lot of people, a lot of money in the project.

454
00:47:36,360 --> 00:47:39,360
 It's already expensive project and we cannot go back right now.

455
00:47:39,360 --> 00:47:42,360
 So this is, this is the scenario that we fear.

456
00:47:42,360 --> 00:47:54,360
 So you fear that you would, uh, invest a lot of money, but at the end, uh, the prompt project will fail and, uh, the money investment.

457
00:47:54,360 --> 00:47:55,360
 No, no, no, no, no.

458
00:47:55,360 --> 00:47:58,360
 We fear that central banks will invest a lot of time and money.

459
00:47:58,360 --> 00:47:59,360
 Okay.

460
00:47:59,360 --> 00:48:03,360
 And then they will impose the digital Euro project to commercial banks and they will say, okay, this is it.

461
00:48:03,360 --> 00:48:08,360
 You have to fit in without asking the commercial banks, what do you think?

462
00:48:08,360 --> 00:48:09,360
 Which are the main issues?

463
00:48:09,360 --> 00:48:12,360
 Uh, how can we solve the main issue?

464
00:48:12,360 --> 00:48:13,360
 So yeah.

465
00:48:13,360 --> 00:48:14,360
 Because it's very interesting.

466
00:48:14,360 --> 00:48:20,360
 But, uh, before that, I would like, uh, to, uh, to hear that the voice of academia.

467
00:48:20,360 --> 00:48:30,360
 So could you please tell us, uh, so from which angle are you looking at the digital Euro and, uh, what are your views about it?

468
00:48:30,360 --> 00:48:33,360
 First of all, thank you for invitation.

469
00:48:33,360 --> 00:48:48,360
 And, uh, I am very happy to say that, uh, our research unit at the University of Florence starts since the beginning of monitoring the develop of a central bank, a digital currency around the world.

470
00:48:48,360 --> 00:49:04,360
 So we, uh, thought that there was something that, uh, we should check and monitor closely because definitely we bring many change if it will be implemented.

471
00:49:04,360 --> 00:49:05,360
 That's how we said.

472
00:49:05,360 --> 00:49:26,360
 And, uh, our research, uh, at the beginning, uh, uh, was, uh, trying to, uh, develop a system and then we call the universal access device that was able to have in the same, um, hardware, both for the, uh, identity, uh, features, then the, um, a means of payment.

473
00:49:26,360 --> 00:49:39,360
 And this tool, uh, get rid of the, um, other, uh, element that comes from, uh, not European, uh, company.

474
00:49:39,360 --> 00:49:46,360
 So our idea was very, uh, focused on the sovereignty of the Europe.

475
00:49:46,360 --> 00:49:49,360
 So we, that was our first project.

476
00:49:49,360 --> 00:49:54,360
 And we published that since, uh, and that was in 2020.

477
00:49:54,360 --> 00:50:10,360
 And we, uh, also after that, we continue our research and we engage with the academia around the world and, um, exploring not only the central bank digital currency, but the digital asset in general.

478
00:50:10,360 --> 00:50:22,360
 So a broad, uh, analysis and that, uh, at the end, uh, we, at the end of this project, we published just last month, a book.

479
00:50:22,360 --> 00:50:25,360
 And, uh, and for us, it's a starting point.

480
00:50:25,360 --> 00:50:33,360
 The book is a starting point in the sense that it's something that we really need to go deeply and work.

481
00:50:33,360 --> 00:50:44,360
 Uh, I think the academia should be also be listened from the European central bank in the sense that we definitely, we have other interpretation.

482
00:50:44,360 --> 00:50:53,360
 Some interpretation are same, other of a different angle, but definitely we think that is something that we have to pursue.

483
00:50:53,360 --> 00:50:54,360
 Okay.

484
00:50:54,360 --> 00:50:55,360
 So great.

485
00:50:55,360 --> 00:51:02,360
 Uh, so we have heard a little bit different, uh, uh, viewpoints on digital euros.

486
00:51:02,360 --> 00:51:11,360
 So I would let, uh, now Mr. Whitlocks maybe to comment on the voice of, uh, Croatian bankers association.

487
00:51:11,360 --> 00:51:21,360
 So, uh, did you already take the, the commercial banks on board and have you, do you listen to them or communicate with them regularly?

488
00:51:21,360 --> 00:51:22,360
 So.

489
00:51:22,360 --> 00:51:23,360
 Yes.

490
00:51:23,360 --> 00:51:31,360
 So, um, so I, I, I'm a bit disappointed that you say that we do don't talk, uh, uh, to the banks.

491
00:51:31,360 --> 00:51:32,360
 We talk to all stakeholders.

492
00:51:32,360 --> 00:51:40,360
 So we had in the investigation phase, we had a market advisory group where the majority of the, uh, participants were experts from the financial sector.

493
00:51:40,360 --> 00:51:42,360
 They were there on their own terms.

494
00:51:42,360 --> 00:51:53,360
 But we have also in the whole of the, uh, uh, investigation phase, I think on a, roughly on a monthly basis interacted with the European retail payments board, where we have all the stakeholders.

495
00:51:53,360 --> 00:51:58,460
 kaži meršants, kaži konsumers, kaži banki, kaži non-banki, kaži PSPs.

496
00:51:58,460 --> 00:52:05,040
 Uža da je njegovati za gledanje, da je za gledanje za gledanje za gledanje.

497
00:52:05,040 --> 00:52:08,100
 Naši je bilaterali interchanges za gledanje za gledanje za gledanje.

498
00:52:08,100 --> 00:52:11,500
 Naši je gledanje za gledanje za gledanje.

499
00:52:11,500 --> 00:52:13,880
 To je uvijek na gledanje na svojnju.

500
00:52:13,880 --> 00:52:20,340
 Naši je uvijek za gledanje za gledanje za gledanje na svojnju.

501
00:52:20,340 --> 00:52:23,780
 In the rulebook development group, as I just mentioned, which is about standards,

502
00:52:23,780 --> 00:52:26,720
 the banks are also very well represented.

503
00:52:26,720 --> 00:52:31,160
 They are currently reviewing the work that they have done together with us,

504
00:52:31,160 --> 00:52:33,000
 with all the stakeholders last year.

505
00:52:33,000 --> 00:52:36,740
 So there is a lot of interaction.

506
00:52:36,740 --> 00:52:44,900
 And there is also, so we, I think we invest a lot in the interaction

507
00:52:44,900 --> 00:52:49,840
 and we also listen and we are transparent.

508
00:52:50,340 --> 00:52:55,480
 That's not to say that we have completely found solutions to everything.

509
00:52:55,480 --> 00:53:00,240
 And I don't want to take that away, but I want to take away the idea

510
00:53:00,240 --> 00:53:03,420
 that we will do something that's not open and transparent.

511
00:53:03,420 --> 00:53:06,560
 And in parallel, the legislative discussion is ongoing

512
00:53:06,560 --> 00:53:10,780
 on which I know the banks are also heavily in front.

513
00:53:11,380 --> 00:53:15,640
 So on a European level, what we get back is that the banks say,

514
00:53:15,640 --> 00:53:20,120
 what they say is we support the digital euro.

515
00:53:20,120 --> 00:53:23,560
 We understand it's important, but we have concerns.

516
00:53:24,720 --> 00:53:31,220
 And concerns are, I think, roughly in two areas.

517
00:53:31,220 --> 00:53:38,600
 So one is about the impact on the liquidity, and that's one point, and on the holding limits.

518
00:53:38,600 --> 00:53:46,760
 So to say there is that we have already included in the design quite a number of features

519
00:53:46,760 --> 00:53:52,580
 in order to address that concern because we also want financial stability.

520
00:53:52,580 --> 00:53:55,480
 It's in our mandate, so we are committed to that as well.

521
00:53:55,480 --> 00:53:58,720
 So those are the points that were on the slides, like no remuneration,

522
00:53:58,720 --> 00:54:02,080
 that there would be a holding limit, that there's this reverse waterfall.

523
00:54:03,680 --> 00:54:10,380
 So that is on one side, and then on the other side, there's the concern about the fit

524
00:54:10,380 --> 00:54:11,920
 in the ecosystem, as I call it.

525
00:54:11,920 --> 00:54:15,100
 So how would this work together with private solutions?

526
00:54:15,100 --> 00:54:19,260
 Also there, as I tried to explain, we think there's really a benefit,

527
00:54:19,260 --> 00:54:22,840
 and they can strengthen each other instead of compete with each other.

528
00:54:22,840 --> 00:54:26,000
 On both, we need to further discuss.

529
00:54:27,000 --> 00:54:36,660
 So on the holding limit in the preparation phase, we have a work planned to do the modeling.

530
00:54:36,660 --> 00:54:41,860
 So what would be the models that we would develop that at a certain point in time

531
00:54:41,860 --> 00:54:47,640
 we could establish the holding limit, and that we really want to do also

532
00:54:47,640 --> 00:54:51,340
 in close cooperation with market participants.

533
00:54:51,340 --> 00:54:56,860
 So also via the European Retail Payments Board, we will have this on the agenda

534
00:54:56,860 --> 00:54:58,340
 from April.

535
00:54:58,340 --> 00:55:04,400
 So I indeed think where there is more work to do, but I truly believe that the digital

536
00:55:04,400 --> 00:55:11,780
 euro is extremely important for Europe, but also really brings benefits not only for the

537
00:55:11,780 --> 00:55:17,260
 consumers and the merchants, which is important as itself, but I think also for the banking sector.

538
00:55:17,260 --> 00:55:24,260
 So I do trust that with further exchanges, we will find the digital euro, that also the

539
00:55:24,260 --> 00:55:27,000
 banking associations would be very happy to distribute.

540
00:55:27,000 --> 00:55:29,520
 So thank you very much for that answer.

541
00:55:29,520 --> 00:55:38,360
 And I think that the reason for organizing such panels is not only to express our views and send it,

542
00:55:38,360 --> 00:55:48,560
 send them to the audience and to a general public, but also to establish relationships among ourselves and to build

543
00:55:48,560 --> 00:55:58,980
 trust and trust and to maybe to find the points where we disagree, but also the ways how to communicate

544
00:55:58,980 --> 00:55:59,680
 about them.

545
00:55:59,680 --> 00:56:10,040
 But I will still dwell with you a little bit and ask you about the counterfactual.

546
00:56:10,040 --> 00:56:32,940
 So we see from everything that you have said that the digital euro project is well underway and it will, well, result in the implementation of digital euro quite soon, not in a very short run, but quite soon.

547
00:56:33,300 --> 00:56:41,620
 But what if not, how would the European payment landscape look like if we don't introduce digital euro?

548
00:56:41,620 --> 00:56:45,580
 Before I go to the question, let me be more precise.

549
00:56:45,580 --> 00:56:55,260
 So there's currently still discussion on the legislation and that will first need to finalize before the governing council can, will only consider to decide the digital euro.

550
00:56:55,260 --> 00:57:04,900
 So there's still, before we will be completely sure that there will be a digital euro, the legislation first need to be finalized and only then a decision of the governing council.

551
00:57:04,900 --> 00:57:10,260
 So there's still some step to take before there will really truly be a digital euro.

552
00:57:10,260 --> 00:57:21,580
 But in the counterfactual, I think we get a lot of the questions on, okay, but what is currently wrong?

553
00:57:21,580 --> 00:57:29,160
 Uh, but I think we need to look not in a two or three years, this is really about a period of time or five years or 10 years or 20 years from now.

554
00:57:29,160 --> 00:57:41,080
 Um, and currently, um, uh, we will probably be in a society where, and, uh, uh, there will still be cash, but people will live much more in a digitalized world.

555
00:57:41,080 --> 00:57:43,980
 So in e-commerce you go, you, you can't pay cash.

556
00:57:43,980 --> 00:57:51,160
 So you need to pay digitally and also in, uh, in other environments, digital payments will become more dominant.

557
00:57:51,580 --> 00:57:58,000
 Um, currently we have a system where you have cash and you have, uh, uh, a big to payment.

558
00:57:58,000 --> 00:58:07,160
 So, but if we would not do anything that we would live in a world where we have only private companies that would be able to provide payment solutions.

559
00:58:07,160 --> 00:58:13,880
 So this means that if you want to pay, you need to put your money at such an institution.

560
00:58:13,880 --> 00:58:22,540
 Um, and currently we assume this to be our European banks, we all, uh, love, um, but we see big tax becoming more and more dominantly.

561
00:58:22,540 --> 00:58:30,580
 So it's not a given, uh, uh, that they, that in 20 or 30 years from now, uh, uh, that they are the dominant.

562
00:58:30,580 --> 00:58:36,000
 Uh, and so maybe then we, people need to give their money to these players in order to be able to pay.

563
00:58:36,000 --> 00:58:46,540
 And we believe that being able to pay is a public good, uh, and therefore it's important that you can also pay with central bank money also in a digital form.

564
00:58:47,920 --> 00:59:01,160
 Um, having said that also in the, in the current environment, uh, the current dependency of, uh, uh, uh, of non-European schemes, um, is extremely high.

565
00:59:01,160 --> 00:59:09,860
 Uh, and fast forward in 10, 20 years, do we feel comfortable that our payments are really provide, uh, provided not by Europe?

566
00:59:09,860 --> 00:59:19,820
 There is no jurisdiction that is so dependent for something so crucial for its society, uh, um, than we have in Europe.

567
00:59:19,820 --> 00:59:31,100
 And then last but not least, uh, we have not been able, the banking sector have not been able to deliver a truly one pan-European solution, digital solution.

568
00:59:31,100 --> 00:59:35,740
 So, um, fast forward, it's important that it's there.

569
00:59:35,740 --> 00:59:36,360
 Okay.

570
00:59:36,360 --> 00:59:37,220
 Thank you very much.

571
00:59:37,820 --> 00:59:39,780
 So, uh, Simon, the next question.

572
00:59:39,780 --> 00:59:45,960
 So, uh, recently you had one conference, uh, in Slovenia about a digital euro introduction.

573
00:59:45,960 --> 00:59:52,980
 So, uh, people in Slovenia have already got this message, message that this project is underway.

574
00:59:52,980 --> 00:59:59,180
 So, uh, can you tell us about the, the impressions and the sentiments after the conference?

575
00:59:59,180 --> 01:00:01,740
 What kind of feedback did you get?

576
01:00:01,740 --> 01:00:07,780
 And, uh, can you also tell us what will exactly change for the Slovenian, uh,

577
01:00:07,820 --> 01:00:09,960
 of people once the digital euro is introduced?

578
01:00:09,960 --> 01:00:15,960
 Indeed, we have, uh, had a large conference in December last year.

579
01:00:15,960 --> 01:00:22,780
 It was a high-level conference attended by six governors of not only the region, but also from the politics.

580
01:00:23,780 --> 01:00:29,220
 And, um, um, uh, it had, uh, a large echo, uh, in the media.

581
01:00:29,220 --> 01:00:36,420
 So, people are now familiar that something is going on, but of course they don't understand all that it does.

582
01:00:36,920 --> 01:00:49,720
 Even, uh, I would like to relate to the banking association of Croatia, when I had first discussions with the supervisory board of the bank association of Slovenia a few years ago.

583
01:00:49,720 --> 01:00:59,080
 And, uh, they were claiming, we already have digital euro, what do you think it is in the account of the, uh, consumers, uh, with us?

584
01:00:59,080 --> 01:01:01,220
 It's digital, it's digital euro.

585
01:01:01,220 --> 01:01:08,620
 And it is difficult to explain the difference between commercial bank money and central bank money.

586
01:01:08,860 --> 01:01:12,160
 So, I believe that communication will be crucial.

587
01:01:12,160 --> 01:01:20,220
 We should not explain to normal people from the street the difference between central bank money and commercial bank money.

588
01:01:20,220 --> 01:01:23,560
 But we should use the narrative of digital cash.

589
01:01:23,560 --> 01:01:36,060
 Digital cash with some value-added features and same level of privacy, uh, excellent user experience.

590
01:01:36,860 --> 01:01:41,300
 And, of course, um, it should be adapted to the digital age.

591
01:01:41,300 --> 01:01:46,320
 So, when they hear digital cash, it is something different.

592
01:01:46,320 --> 01:01:49,080
 It is not a deposit with a commercial bank.

593
01:01:49,080 --> 01:01:51,360
 And we are going that way.

594
01:01:51,360 --> 01:02:01,300
 And, uh, for this, we also need, um, from the very beginning, it is my own opinion, also the offline version of, uh, digital euro.

595
01:02:01,300 --> 01:02:06,760
 Because this is a true replication of cash in a digital world.

596
01:02:06,860 --> 01:02:11,700
 We cannot add offline some, at some point later.

597
01:02:11,700 --> 01:02:13,440
 So, this is very important.

598
01:02:14,300 --> 01:02:22,100
 And, uh, to describe Swinia landscape a little bit, uh, deeper, also relating to the Bank Association of Croatia.

599
01:02:22,100 --> 01:02:26,020
 Instant payments are very important, uh, at the moment.

600
01:02:26,020 --> 01:02:31,520
 We have, uh, that EPC scheme for instant payments now for many years.

601
01:02:31,520 --> 01:02:37,160
 Uh, also, the euro system has established tips for pan-European instant payments.

602
01:02:37,160 --> 01:02:39,540
 And people are getting used to it.

603
01:02:39,540 --> 01:02:45,060
 So, digital euro will be based on the principles of the instant payments.

604
01:02:45,640 --> 01:02:54,340
 Once people get familiar with instant payments, and instant payments are always linked to a bank account with your commercial bank.

605
01:02:54,340 --> 01:03:00,720
 So, this is an area where commercial banks should see advantage and opportunity.

606
01:03:00,980 --> 01:03:04,520
 Because it is not going to some big tax or somewhere.

607
01:03:04,520 --> 01:03:09,380
 It is linked to your normal current account with a commercial bank.

608
01:03:09,380 --> 01:03:15,000
 And, uh, in Slovenia, we have a very successful national scheme for instant payments.

609
01:03:15,000 --> 01:03:25,800
 Half a million Slovenians, it is more than 25% of population, have already been using our instant payment application.

610
01:03:26,380 --> 01:03:37,560
 And this is important to get a user experience, which will be very similar than in the environment of, uh, of, um, digital euro.

611
01:03:37,560 --> 01:03:49,260
 And, as many of you may be familiar, the euro system is supporting very much also private initiatives in establishing a pan-European instant payment solutions.

612
01:03:49,260 --> 01:03:56,000
 We have, uh, some, uh, activities of the EPI, European Payments Initiative.

613
01:03:56,380 --> 01:04:02,960
 Some, uh, some, uh, mobile operators, uh, wanting to achieve interoperability and so on.

614
01:04:02,960 --> 01:04:09,360
 But it is not, uh, taking grounds, uh, at least not in a pan-European context.

615
01:04:09,360 --> 01:04:22,860
 So, I believe that banks should see normal instant payments in digital euro as complementary, um, topics or issues.

616
01:04:23,660 --> 01:04:30,860
 And, uh, this is also very important for merchants, I have, I have to say.

617
01:04:30,860 --> 01:04:34,100
 Slovenians, Slovenians are only 2 million.

618
01:04:34,100 --> 01:04:38,520
 In the euro area, we have 350 million, uh, citizens.

619
01:04:38,520 --> 01:04:46,440
 Uh, and we should, of course, have a unique, harmonized user experience.

620
01:04:46,900 --> 01:04:49,320
 I cannot pay with Slovenian solution.

621
01:04:49,320 --> 01:04:51,300
 I have it, I like it abroad.

622
01:04:51,300 --> 01:04:52,180
 No way.

623
01:04:52,180 --> 01:05:01,640
 Even customers, Slovenians, customers of N26 or Revolut cannot use it because they cannot, uh, access this, uh, scheme.

624
01:05:01,640 --> 01:05:06,140
 So, for merchants, it will be very important to have a digital euro.

625
01:05:06,800 --> 01:05:17,200
 Because Slovenia is, according to some bank, uh, the France studies ranked amongst the highest merchant, uh, fee countries in the Europe.

626
01:05:18,480 --> 01:05:23,940
 We have to know that digital euro will not have its own scheme to be paid.

627
01:05:23,940 --> 01:05:30,480
 At least not in terms as, uh, visa scheme or MC scheme are paid for today.

628
01:05:30,880 --> 01:05:40,900
 I like to say that if you're looking Champions League in football, there are always some advertisements of one card scheme around the stadium.

629
01:05:40,900 --> 01:05:49,120
 I doubt that the digital euro will have such, uh, uh, panos around, uh, the soccer field.

630
01:05:49,120 --> 01:05:50,600
 I'm not sure.

631
01:05:50,600 --> 01:05:54,380
 Uh, so, it should be cheaper for merchants.

632
01:05:54,980 --> 01:06:00,140
 And, uh, the acquiring banks should not, uh, gain some extra profits out of it.

633
01:06:00,140 --> 01:06:05,420
 It should be cheaper because we will not charge any special scheme fee.

634
01:06:05,420 --> 01:06:14,940
 And, uh, what is important, it is expected, according to the proposal of the Commission, to be also, to also have a status of legal tender.

635
01:06:14,940 --> 01:06:17,080
 It is very important.

636
01:06:17,080 --> 01:06:20,560
 And, uh, to conclude this intervention,

637
01:06:20,960 --> 01:06:27,420
 I believe that banks should seize the opportunity today having instant payments.

638
01:06:27,420 --> 01:06:32,780
 Offering an application, a solution to customers,

639
01:06:32,780 --> 01:06:36,960
 still trying to achieve pan-European reach.

640
01:06:36,960 --> 01:06:42,120
 And then digital euro will be just something next to it.

641
01:06:42,120 --> 01:06:46,460
 It should not crowd out the private instant payment solutions.

642
01:06:47,240 --> 01:06:55,280
 So, um, this is, this is my, um, opinion, uh, and I believe that banks should not be afraid of it.

643
01:06:55,280 --> 01:07:01,440
 Uh, just last, uh, sentence in this, um, in replying to this question.

644
01:07:01,440 --> 01:07:08,800
 Can you imagine N26 or Revolut being in existence without SEPA?

645
01:07:09,580 --> 01:07:22,320
 So, uh, I cannot, uh, I cannot, uh, and now digital euro as a next stage is coming again, offering niche players to get, to gain pan-European reach from the day one.

646
01:07:22,320 --> 01:07:24,720
 Okay.

647
01:07:24,720 --> 01:07:25,840
 Thank you very much.

648
01:07:25,840 --> 01:07:32,120
 Uh, before, before turning back to Tamara and checking whether the opinion has changed.

649
01:07:32,120 --> 01:07:37,820
 Uh, uh, let us go to, uh, Alexi.

650
01:07:37,820 --> 01:07:50,740
 So in, in Finland, uh, the society is a little bit different, uh, than in, in Slovenia or Croatia, but also the, uh, the economy is different.

651
01:07:50,740 --> 01:07:56,500
 And, uh, in, in Finland, you have quite developed a digital and fintech, uh, landscape.

652
01:07:56,500 --> 01:08:04,800
 So do you see any role of, uh, fintech companies in digital euro or, uh, any opportunities for them?

653
01:08:04,800 --> 01:08:08,680
 Yes, every country is different.

654
01:08:08,680 --> 01:08:15,400
 Um, and that's not to say that Finland is necessarily the most advanced or, or perfect.

655
01:08:15,520 --> 01:08:18,080
 We, we, we have our challenges as well.

656
01:08:18,080 --> 01:08:23,960
 Um, so the digitization hasn't, um, always resulted in the, in the kind of perfect outcome.

657
01:08:23,960 --> 01:08:43,800
 Um, so, so one of those is when we see what's happened in the fintech, in the fintech industry, especially smaller companies that have come to the market in recent years, as actually Simon mentioned, uh, there was an idea that they could offer services that compete with banks.

658
01:08:43,800 --> 01:08:49,100
 That there would be some sort of competition between, uh, payment services and services offered by banks.

659
01:08:49,100 --> 01:08:54,160
 What actually happened is that they are very dependent on banks to offer those services at the moment.

660
01:08:54,160 --> 01:09:04,560
 It's, it's practically impossible for a fintech company to build services and offer services without building a relationship with a bank to handle customer funds, to do payments.

661
01:09:05,080 --> 01:09:14,620
 Um, and that would, what has happened is a lot of the kind of business benefits, um, are not actually going to the fintechs themselves, but it's actually going to banks.

662
01:09:14,620 --> 01:09:25,240
 So the bank's becoming even, even stronger than, than, than before, even though maybe five, 10 years ago, we thought that banks would be disrupted by fintech companies and there would be new competition.

663
01:09:25,240 --> 01:09:33,580
 But that, that, that hasn't really happened because the, um, infrastructures and the, and the payment landscape doesn't really fully allow that.

664
01:09:33,960 --> 01:09:43,020
 So what the digital euro is actually doing is precisely that is it's offering a complete, completely different alternative to managing payments.

665
01:09:43,020 --> 01:09:56,240
 Um, so for a smaller company, um, it should be less costly and less burdensome to build a service around the digital, around digital euro accounts, because you don't practically actually handle customer money.

666
01:09:56,240 --> 01:10:07,220
 The money stays in the central bank, um, so you don't actually have to, um, open, open a bank account with a commercial bank to do, uh, safeguarding of customer funds and to do payments.

667
01:10:07,220 --> 01:10:13,140
 There is an alternative with the digital euro, so you can actually build the services entirely around digital euro accounts.

668
01:10:13,140 --> 01:10:19,560
 And that makes it, um, from the fintechs perspective, uh, kind of more, uh, kind of a lighter model.

669
01:10:19,560 --> 01:10:29,360
 So it doesn't require quite as much, um, administrative burden and also business, the business benefits are much better because the euro system is not going to charge you any scheme fees or anything like that.

670
01:10:29,360 --> 01:10:33,360
 So you can basically use that as a sort of open platform to, to build services.

671
01:10:33,360 --> 01:10:35,860
 So that's, that's sort of one aspect at least.

672
01:10:35,860 --> 01:10:43,520
 And then maybe to also comment on, um, because we, we also, our banks have also expressed some concerns.

673
01:10:43,520 --> 01:10:54,420
 Um, and, and, and one point that, uh, I usually want to point out is that we're, we're talking about, um, the growth of, uh, the business into the future.

674
01:10:54,420 --> 01:10:59,860
 So we're not really too much worried about, it's not a zero sum game, but I think that's the point.

675
01:10:59,860 --> 01:11:08,680
 So the introduction of the digital euro is not going to suck deposits from banks or money from cash the way it is now.

676
01:11:08,680 --> 01:11:24,280
 What we have to look at is the growth of money from now into the future and how that is divided between new commercial bank deposits, new cash, and digital euro is going to get some share of that growth.

677
01:11:24,280 --> 01:11:31,840
 So we're not actually touching, um, there's no, not necessarily any decline in the current levels of deposits or cash.

678
01:11:31,840 --> 01:11:43,840
 We're talking about how the kind of new economy is going to be divided between these three different forms of money, because when we look back 20 years, that's exactly the same that's happened.

679
01:11:43,840 --> 01:11:50,080
 So deposits have grown very much, but cash has also grown very much and they haven't really competed with each other.

680
01:11:50,080 --> 01:11:50,860
 They're both grown.

681
01:11:50,860 --> 01:12:00,480
 So in the future from now into, into the future, that growth is going to be divided between three different forms of money, cash, digital euro, and bank deposits.

682
01:12:01,200 --> 01:12:05,860
 Can you tell us what is the level of discussion in Finland a bit about digital euro?

683
01:12:05,860 --> 01:12:15,820
 Uh, is it still a new topic or, uh, um, people talk about it in their, uh, well, well, drinking coffee.

684
01:12:15,820 --> 01:12:18,660
 If you drink coffee in a coffee, it's like us.

685
01:12:18,660 --> 01:12:19,740
 I don't know that.

686
01:12:19,740 --> 01:12:27,060
 It's a topic that, um, people who work in the industry know about very well.

687
01:12:27,060 --> 01:12:34,140
 They, they, they follow it, but I would say the general public, there has been some news, um, some press coverage of the digital euro.

688
01:12:34,140 --> 01:12:41,060
 People have noticed it, but, um, maybe this, the discussion isn't very lively at the moment.

689
01:12:41,060 --> 01:12:46,560
 And I think that has to do with, from the consumers, from the citizens' point of view, we have to be honest.

690
01:12:46,560 --> 01:12:51,360
 There isn't necessarily much novelty in introducing the digital euro.

691
01:12:51,360 --> 01:12:58,720
 They, they've seen what it's about and they think, okay, that's one more option to all the other services that I, that we already have.

692
01:12:58,960 --> 01:13:08,300
 So from our perspective at the Bank of Finland, we see it maybe a bit more as an kind of infrastructure project, a kind of back-end project rather than a front-end project.

693
01:13:08,300 --> 01:13:18,400
 Uh, so for us, the fact that it brings resilience, brings an alternative payment rail, and it brings more competition, those are maybe the key arguments for us.

694
01:13:18,400 --> 01:13:25,240
 And we, we're not even trying to convince the public that they are going to getting some kind of completely novel product.

695
01:13:25,240 --> 01:13:25,540
 I see.

696
01:13:25,540 --> 01:13:26,760
 Thank you very much.

697
01:13:26,760 --> 01:13:38,120
 Now, Professor Barresi, so, uh, from your point of view, what would be the economic, but also, uh, social, uh, impacts of digital euro?

698
01:13:38,840 --> 01:13:47,600
 Uh, I think this, this, this, uh, social part is, uh, very important as well, not only the economic, so social and, or societal.

699
01:13:47,600 --> 01:13:55,280
 First of all, I would like to add something from my previous, uh, speakers and I agree 100% to what they said.

700
01:13:55,280 --> 01:14:04,080
 And the first I want to say about the instant payment, instant payment from the perspective of the central bank.

701
01:14:04,080 --> 01:14:09,320
 We, we, we can, with the digital euro, we can have a, an instant finality of payment.

702
01:14:09,320 --> 01:14:18,780
 So this is crucial and this is a very important, and it's something that is a risk-free payment because it's the liability of the central bank.

703
01:14:18,780 --> 01:14:26,880
 This is something that people have to be educated, to understand, so that this, this is something that could be a social point of view.

704
01:14:27,440 --> 01:14:34,580
 And I would like to add what I said in my previous, uh, speaker about the importance of payment service providers.

705
01:14:34,580 --> 01:14:36,020
 They are not in contrast.

706
01:14:36,020 --> 01:14:43,080
 The, the way of working should be in harmonizing with the, the, the central banks.

707
01:14:43,080 --> 01:14:55,140
 So, because we have, uh, regulation, we have, uh, the directive, the new proposal for the digital euro mentioned the second payment service directive.

708
01:14:55,480 --> 01:15:05,080
 And of course, this is something that they, the bank have to implement, but we also have now the proposal for the third payment service directive.

709
01:15:05,080 --> 01:15:18,280
 So we have to take in consideration that the, the way of, of the payment service providers is not opposite of what the, the central banks does.

710
01:15:18,460 --> 01:15:23,640
 So we need to have a cooperation, that's, that is the idea of the academia.

711
01:15:23,640 --> 01:15:34,080
 And we, if we are able to build something together, I think that the result could be much, much more valuable.

712
01:15:34,080 --> 01:15:38,700
 That's easier, of course, our, um, point of view.

713
01:15:39,100 --> 01:15:47,820
 And, um, you are asking about the, the social, uh, social, uh, elements that are, we, we are thinking about the privacy.

714
01:15:47,820 --> 01:15:55,120
 We are thinking, like, uh, Ms. Ellen said, uh, we are thinking about also the, the fraud.

715
01:15:55,360 --> 01:16:00,900
 And, um, this is something that they have to be, the consumer, the consumer has to be protected.

716
01:16:00,900 --> 01:16:12,800
 And, um, of course, we can also think about the, uh, inclusion, but the inclusion goes with the, uh, financial education, I think.

717
01:16:13,360 --> 01:16:23,280
 So, uh, um, at least for Italy, we, uh, we don't have so much, um, answer on this side.

718
01:16:23,280 --> 01:16:29,100
 And we don't have, uh, uh, uh, really educated people that understand what we are talking about.

719
01:16:29,620 --> 01:16:37,160
 And, um, if they, they make a confusion, if they ask about the digital asset, they, they think of Bitcoin.

720
01:16:37,160 --> 01:16:55,360
 So, they confuse the digital euro with the, with the cryptocurrency for, so if you don't, you are not in an educated, uh, um, uh, contest, you, you have this kind of, uh, answer back.

721
01:16:55,360 --> 01:17:04,580
 So, this is something that we think we should start from the school, from the very beginning, try to express what is the difference?

722
01:17:04,580 --> 01:17:10,560
 What does it mean to have a new kind of digital form of euro?

723
01:17:10,560 --> 01:17:21,100
 And, uh, on the same time, we can say that, unfortunately, uh, we have, uh, unbanked and we have also underbanked.

724
01:17:21,100 --> 01:17:28,740
 So, the digital euro could be useful also to help the micro-imprenditorial, uh, activities.

725
01:17:28,740 --> 01:17:37,120
 And, of course, the, I'm talking about Italy, but women are really the most unbanked people in Italy.

726
01:17:37,120 --> 01:17:41,700
 And this is something that should, should be changed.

727
01:17:42,240 --> 01:17:49,540
 And, um, and I think that this could be, uh, really, I mean, uh, of, uh, inclusion.

728
01:17:49,540 --> 01:18:02,520
 And, um, as we said within the light that you show us, there is some kind of, of, uh, public authority that is designated to help people that are not able to do by themselves.

729
01:18:02,520 --> 01:18:12,360
 So, uh, this kind of, uh, um, boarding in the, um, account of, to the, uh, um, that have the digital euro.

730
01:18:12,360 --> 01:18:15,880
 So, this is something that we should really work on.

731
01:18:15,880 --> 01:18:24,960
 So, do you have any advice for us, uh, central bankers, uh, on, uh, how exactly to promote the financial literacy

732
01:18:24,960 --> 01:18:32,600
 in order to make, uh, digital euro more easily, uh, adopted by, by the people?

733
01:18:32,600 --> 01:18:39,100
 I think that the best things is starting with the school, just from the beginning in an easy way.

734
01:18:39,100 --> 01:18:41,800
 And also all the media can help us.

735
01:18:41,800 --> 01:18:51,760
 And, uh, in academia, we try to, uh, give, of course, the specific, uh, I can say explanation,

736
01:18:51,760 --> 01:18:57,540
 but it's something that is a more higher level on people that they take some kind of course

737
01:18:57,540 --> 01:19:05,500
 and the specific on this, uh, on digital assets in general and central bank digital currency in specific.

738
01:19:05,500 --> 01:19:09,800
 But, uh, the problem is that it's not that educated people.

739
01:19:09,800 --> 01:19:17,580
 The problem is the people that has no clue what is, uh, because it has not a financial background,

740
01:19:17,580 --> 01:19:24,040
 on the beta financial, I think, not in the, in the, in the level of, uh, investor on the trademark.

741
01:19:24,040 --> 01:19:30,360
 I, that's why I think it's something that to be really, yeah, it's a really hot topic.

742
01:19:30,360 --> 01:19:32,820
 Thank you, Tamara.

743
01:19:32,820 --> 01:19:41,440
 Uh, so you said that, uh, the banks see some challenges or risks with, uh, the introduction of digital euro,

744
01:19:41,440 --> 01:19:46,100
 but, uh, do they see any opportunities, uh, with the digital euro?

745
01:19:46,100 --> 01:19:51,920
 First, yeah, I will refer to, to what was said, uh, on the panel.

746
01:19:51,920 --> 01:19:56,060
 Uh, so Ms. Baresi said one key word for me and it's cooperation.

747
01:19:56,060 --> 01:20:06,000
 I think that for the successful implementation of the project, we all need to cooperate it from academia, central bankers, commercial bankers, uh, consumers.

748
01:20:06,000 --> 01:20:17,640
 So cooperation, I think it's, it's a key word here, uh, the other things other that you mentioned, which I think it, it's of key importance that we see the, the real person behind the project.

749
01:20:17,640 --> 01:20:22,160
 Uh, and that's, that's one of the really, uh, important things.

750
01:20:22,160 --> 01:20:27,160
 The other things that Simon mentioned, uh, were payment services.

751
01:20:27,160 --> 01:20:51,540
 With regard to payment services, uh, when we had this, uh, introductory education, uh, with creation central bank, then I would say the 90% of the questions who are with regard to payment services, what then, what if, uh, there are still, as I understood from this, from this meeting, still a lot, a lot of open questions.

752
01:20:52,740 --> 01:21:00,300
 And, uh, I believe that when we are talking about digital euro, we have to talk also about the open issues.

753
01:21:00,300 --> 01:21:07,900
 Your presentation was great, but I was missing, okay, still open issues that we'll still need to, to handle.

754
01:21:07,900 --> 01:21:15,160
 And I think that here is, here is the, the key that we, that the flow of information is really good.

755
