 And maybe we could use settlement tokens to convert from one currency to another.

1521
02:01:49,120 --> 02:01:52,120
 Maybe as a way to improve upon correspondent banking.

1522
02:01:52,120 --> 02:01:55,120
 Which has lots of problems and costs, as we know.

1523
02:01:55,120 --> 02:02:00,120
 But it doesn't actually address the problem that was raised in the last session at all.

1524
02:02:00,120 --> 02:02:05,120
 Which is the decline of cash and cash-like instruments in domestic payments.

1525
02:02:05,120 --> 02:02:08,120
 So all of these kinds of ideas have been discussed.

1526
02:02:08,120 --> 02:02:19,120
 But what I'd like people to consider is maybe retail CBDC should be cash for the digital age.

1527
02:02:19,120 --> 02:02:20,120
 Right?

1528
02:02:20,120 --> 02:02:26,120
 Maybe we should be looking at CBDC as an opportunity to make cash become digital.

1529
02:02:26,120 --> 02:02:43,120
 Rather than assume that this is something that we need to build bolt upon the existing electronic payment systems that are based upon card networks and interbank push payments and so on.

1530
02:02:43,120 --> 02:02:45,120
 Maybe we need something new.

1531
02:02:45,120 --> 02:02:58,120
 And if we were to provide a cash-like retail CBDC, I would like to suggest that, you know, in the previous panel, the speakers had said very clearly, it's not going to replace cash.

1532
02:02:58,120 --> 02:03:08,120
 Because we will always need something that we can physically possess and control to be able to give to people in certain kinds of transactions.

1533
02:03:08,120 --> 02:03:11,120
 And it will also not replace bank deposits.

1534
02:03:11,120 --> 02:03:15,120
 Because after all, bank deposits are at some level for banking.

1535
02:03:15,120 --> 02:03:25,120
 And if I want to hold money for any non-negligible amount of time, I might imagine that there is some benefit to having this money be invested.

1536
02:03:25,120 --> 02:03:37,120
 And so it's not really a replacement to physical cash or to bank deposits, but it can be useful as a payment mechanism that can be used in the digital economy.

1537
02:03:37,120 --> 02:03:44,120
 And as we know, the prevailing trend that's facing retail consumers today is the rise of the digital economy.

1538
02:03:44,120 --> 02:03:51,120
 There are throughout the UK and parts of Europe, there are merchants who refuse cash at the point of sale.

1539
02:03:51,120 --> 02:04:06,120
 There are high street shops that close and entirely or perhaps only offer some of their goods online because of the rise of online e-commerce as a substitute for those kinds of services.

1540
02:04:06,120 --> 02:04:10,120
 And in all cases, they need to make some kind of digital payment.

1541
02:04:10,120 --> 02:04:15,120
 But of course, this raises questions about monetary sovereignty.

1542
02:04:15,120 --> 02:04:26,120
 And we also raise questions about whether ordinary households and individuals can actually directly hold central bank obligations.

1543
02:04:26,120 --> 02:04:29,120
 Right now, the only way to do this is with cash.

1544
02:04:29,120 --> 02:04:42,120
 So if we look at it this way, maybe we can think of retail CBDC as being an opportunity to build something that's non-custodial, right?

1545
02:04:42,120 --> 02:04:57,120
 People often assume that cash is non-custodial and physical and the alternative to cash must be custodial and digital, which is what card payments and interbank transfers that we're familiar with in the current institutional framework are.

1546
02:04:57,120 --> 02:05:14,120
 But actually, there's a third way that's not being examined nearly as much as it should, which is this non-custodial aspect of cash combined with the digital aspect of cards and interbank transfers.

1547
02:05:14,120 --> 02:05:21,120
 And because we're missing this in the discussion, we're making assumptions that don't make sense.

1548
02:05:21,120 --> 02:05:30,120
 So when we talk about the digital euro, which came up in the last panel, what we need to understand is the motivation.

1549
02:05:30,120 --> 02:05:41,120
 There's quite a bit of focus on fully offline payments, right, as something that has the right privacy characteristics, as something that has possession.

1550
02:05:41,120 --> 02:05:52,120
 But what's strange is that it's online payments that matter because of the rise of the rise of the digital economy.

1551
02:05:52,120 --> 02:06:08,120
 So if we put a fully offline cash-like CBDC in competition with cash, there has been research that has shown that now we'll have a worse equilibrium than either cash or CBDC alone.

1552
02:06:08,120 --> 02:06:17,120
 So why are we focusing upon the cash-like scenarios of this fully offline case when really what matters is the online case because of the digital economy?

1553
02:06:17,120 --> 02:06:19,120
 So I thought that was strange.

1554
02:06:19,120 --> 02:06:31,120
 I also would like to suggest that there are certified hardware requirements that are implicit that were mentioned in these fully offline digital euro proposal as well.

1555
02:06:31,120 --> 02:06:34,120
 And certified hardware requirements have a number of problems, right?

1556
02:06:34,120 --> 02:06:37,120
 They can't really be tweaked or analyzed.

1557
02:06:37,120 --> 02:06:41,120
 You can't have people build by ordinary users.

1558
02:06:41,120 --> 02:06:43,120
 Ordinary users can't build their own.

1559
02:06:43,120 --> 02:06:44,120
 So that discourages innovation.

1560
02:06:44,120 --> 02:06:50,120
 And the market, of course, gives a privileged position to the device manufacturers, which is problematic.

1561
02:06:50,120 --> 02:06:55,120
 And the relationship is quite sticky because you own your device, which has hardware.

1562
02:06:55,120 --> 02:06:59,120
 You can't dispose of it very easily like you can with even a bank account.

1563
02:06:59,120 --> 02:07:01,120
 And it's a de facto bank account.

1564
02:07:01,120 --> 02:07:06,120
 And, of course, it introduces systemic risk because when it fails, it fails hard.

1565
02:07:06,120 --> 02:07:11,120
 And you're putting a lot-- you're vesting a lot of concern in these-- a lot of trust in these hardware manufacturers.

1566
02:07:11,120 --> 02:07:13,120
 So I'm worried about that as well.

1567
02:07:13,120 --> 02:07:19,120
 And, yes, for the avoidance of doubt, online payments don't have any privacy because you will be tracked.

1568
02:07:19,120 --> 02:07:24,120
 Anyone who looks at your bank-- anyone who looks at their bank statements will know that they're being tracked.

1569
02:07:24,120 --> 02:07:29,120
 So when we talk about this system, I thought that was strange.

1570
02:07:29,120 --> 02:07:32,120
 And, finally, this idea of accounts.

1571
02:07:32,120 --> 02:07:36,120
 Everything is linked to digital euro payment accounts that are managed by de facto custodians.

1572
02:07:36,120 --> 02:07:39,120
 Well, that means that we can't have self-custody.

1573
02:07:39,120 --> 02:07:42,120
 The wallet is linked to the user's identity.

1574
02:07:42,120 --> 02:07:48,120
 And, finally, wallet and users are linked to holding limits, which weren't really justified so well.

1575
02:07:48,120 --> 02:07:53,120
 So inside this proposal, the justification for holding limits was, well, we want to avoid bank runs.

1576
02:07:53,120 --> 02:08:02,120
 Well, this is very strange given the euro, because if we remember back to Grexit, the discussion well before Brexit, when Greece was having problems,

1577
02:08:02,120 --> 02:08:07,120
 it had restricted withdrawals from banks to 60 euros per day, a very small number.

1578
02:08:07,120 --> 02:08:16,120
 And that was quite effective in preventing bank runs in Greece while the Greek government negotiated around this.

1579
02:08:16,120 --> 02:08:20,120
 And this idea that we need holding limits for that purpose doesn't make sense.

1580
02:08:20,120 --> 02:08:27,120
 So then why do we want holding limits when we could just as easily implement withdrawal limits?

1581
02:08:27,120 --> 02:08:32,120
 If we're really concerned about bank runs or systemic problems, withdrawal limits would do it.

1582
02:08:32,120 --> 02:08:35,120
 So I thought that was strange too.

1583
02:08:35,120 --> 02:08:40,120
 But when we look at this, the ECB proposal isn't alone, right?

1584
02:08:40,120 --> 02:08:46,120
 I mean, we have other proposals like in the UK and the US and even China have very similar characteristics.

1585
02:08:46,120 --> 02:08:53,120
 And, and what I'd like to suggest is that this is a political, this is a political discussion.

1586
02:08:53,120 --> 02:08:56,120
 And maybe we need to have this political conversation.

1587
02:08:56,120 --> 02:08:59,120
 And we need to talk about regulations.

1588
02:08:59,120 --> 02:09:03,120
 We need to talk about the potential misconceptions, like what is the European Parliament thinking

1589
02:09:03,120 --> 02:09:10,120
 when they specify certain, when they specify certain rules for how the digital euro would work.

1590
02:09:10,120 --> 02:09:13,120
 And yes, there are businesses involved in this conversation as well.

1591
02:09:13,120 --> 02:09:16,120
 And they have certain interests and certain business models.

1592
02:09:16,120 --> 02:09:22,120
 And it's hard for them to see past those business models into business models of the future.

1593
02:09:22,120 --> 02:09:29,120
 And we need to get them to think in a forward looking way about what it is that we're building, which means that we need to have some leadership politically.

1594
02:09:29,120 --> 02:09:32,120
 And that's a big challenge here.

1595
02:09:32,120 --> 02:09:37,120
 And maybe that means that we need to consider whether we're actually ready for a CBDC at this point.

1596
02:09:37,120 --> 02:09:45,120
 Even if we all agree, and maybe we don't, but even if we all were to agree that we need a CBDC, is the time now?

1597
02:09:45,120 --> 02:09:51,120
 When I look at the proposal saying maybe 2025 will start the implementation phase, how is that even possible?

1598
02:09:51,120 --> 02:09:54,120
 We haven't even agreed on the requirements yet.

1599
02:09:54,120 --> 02:10:04,120
 And I think anyone who's designed engineering systems would, I think, probably agree that you need to figure out what the requirements are before you build a spec,

1600
02:10:04,120 --> 02:10:11,120
 and then you need to get consensus on the spec from stakeholders before you build a prototype and so on.

1601
02:10:11,120 --> 02:10:15,120
 And it seems like we're really moving very fast.

1602
02:10:15,120 --> 02:10:17,120
 I know that people think it's slow.

1603
02:10:17,120 --> 02:10:18,120
 It's not.

1604
02:10:18,120 --> 02:10:23,120
 And people think that we're quite far along this journey, but we're not.

1605
02:10:23,120 --> 02:10:26,120
 There's a lot that we still need to figure out.

1606
02:10:26,120 --> 02:10:32,120
 And in a shifting landscape, doing nothing, unfortunately, might not be a conservative option.

1607
02:10:32,120 --> 02:10:38,120
 And it might not be a conservative option because the digital economy is coming, whether we like it or not.

1608
02:10:38,120 --> 02:10:43,120
 So let's talk about another possible bridge that will help us get there.

1609
02:10:43,120 --> 02:10:45,120
 I mean, there have been people thinking about this.

1610
02:10:45,120 --> 02:10:50,120
 I'm going to talk about one proposal from the BIS, reserve-backed tokens.

1611
02:10:50,120 --> 02:11:06,120
 So, basically, a TRIPAM goal of BIS proposed this idea where maybe private sector banks issue certain tokens that are backed by central bank reserves that are linked to their issuers.

1612
02:11:06,120 --> 02:11:31,120
 So, yes, indeed, not fungible, but, and yes, they do have some potential risks associated with them, but perhaps, but perhaps they actually move the envelope, decreasing the riskiness of the backing by having true central bank reserves back them, but yet also have, but yet still be issued by a private sector institutional issuer.

1613
02:11:31,120 --> 02:11:38,120
 And, and maybe that might potentially provide this kind of bridge that might help.

1614
02:11:38,120 --> 02:11:40,120
 Of course, there are challenges with this.

1615
02:11:40,120 --> 02:11:50,120
 So, if we imagine how the bank, how the balance sheets of the issuer change and the balance sheets of the central bank change after issuing one of these reserve-backed tokens, we can see that there are going to be changes, right?

1616
02:11:50,120 --> 02:12:06,120
 We get new reserve-backed tokens that get minted, but we also see a shift where the bank that's issuing them, their shallow, their balance sheet shrinks a bit, and the central bank balance sheet grows a bit, which raises some questions about where the risk goes.

1617
02:12:06,120 --> 02:12:19,120
 I'm, this is, these are equal size pots, right? The central bank balance sheet grows, and the bank loses a certain amount of loans of equal size. That's interesting. So, maybe there's something going on there.

1618
02:12:19,120 --> 02:12:34,120
 And then, of course, there's the question of how this business model works. When we know that these RBT tokens are supposedly zero risk, wealth, and the reserves are supposedly zero risk, well, let's take a look at this other assets versus capital.

1619
02:12:34,120 --> 02:12:49,120
 So, what is the business here? Is this about collecting, is this about, you know, collecting fees? Is this something else? Is it about some kind of risk of the issuer's credit? I mean, these are questions that we need to answer.

1620
02:12:49,120 --> 02:13:16,120
 And, of course, we have questions about the oversight and the supervision and the regulation of this. And, of course, I want to say this, payments are not banking. Right? When we talk about the role of banks, we think about banking as being taking deposits and making risky investments and perhaps giving depositors some share, some fraction of the income from that.

1621
02:13:16,120 --> 02:13:39,000
 But payments are something different. And there has been research that has shown that over the past two decades or more, we have seen a shift in revenue sources to banks, to private sector banks. Private sector banks, a greater share of their revenue is coming from payments than before.

1622
02:13:39,120 --> 02:13:58,320
 And is, does this bundling of payment service provision with other banking services create systemic risk to this, to the economy at large? Is this actually a risk to us that our payments are now bundled with banking?

1623
02:13:59,600 --> 02:14:13,120
 So, I want to close with some design considerations. So, there are some myths that came up, including some myths that were discussed in the last panel. You know, is it the case that a consumer's balance must always be managed in an account?

1624
02:14:14,480 --> 02:14:29,860
 Well, clearly not, right? I mean, I love pulling out cash in these conversations because what's nice about cash is it's in nobody's account that I am holding this. It's not my, it doesn't have to be in my consumer's account.

1625
02:14:29,860 --> 02:14:50,480
 And this idea that the payer must always be identifiable. Well, I mentioned the FATF travel rule. Well, that's where this debate comes from, right? And what I'd like to suggest is that it's possible for payers to be anonymous and not discoverable and still enforce rules on the transaction.

1626
02:14:50,480 --> 02:15:02,980
 And there are architectures that can allow us to do that. I mentioned Project Torbjorn of the BIS Swiss Center. That is one example of an architecture that needs to be looked at more carefully in this space in terms of privacy model.

1627
02:15:02,980 --> 02:15:11,260
 Now, if you look at the letter of what FATF is recommending, you might say, oh, well, that's no good. It doesn't follow that to the letter.

1628
02:15:11,520 --> 02:15:19,620
 Well, I think we need to have some, some serious discussion about what's getting replaced, which is something that also doesn't follow FATF's guidance to the letter.

1629
02:15:19,620 --> 02:15:28,320
 And this idea that in 1997, FATF had published a recommendation that said that governments should encourage the replacement of cash.

1630
02:15:28,320 --> 02:15:38,000
 So even if the ECB is saying we're not going to replace cash, let's remember that the FATF said two, three decades ago that you should.

1631
02:15:39,640 --> 02:15:45,120
 That's really important because that's the worry that people are having around privacy is really about this.

1632
02:15:45,120 --> 02:15:50,820
 Are we, are people being shoved into having all of their, their, their locations and habits and travels exposed?

1633
02:15:50,820 --> 02:15:52,900
 And the answer is, well, yes.

1634
02:15:52,900 --> 02:15:57,740
 And this question about issuers knowing where all the tokens are.

1635
02:15:57,740 --> 02:16:03,880
 Well, if you can create rules that prevent tokens from being transacted more than once, for example,

1636
02:16:03,880 --> 02:16:10,540
 or create rules that make sure that they, that recipients of money satisfy certain AML criteria and so on,

1637
02:16:10,540 --> 02:16:16,960
 you can actually enforce very strong compliance rules without knowing exactly where every single token is.

1638
02:16:16,960 --> 02:16:21,140
 So when people say that they have to know, don't believe them.

1639
02:16:22,460 --> 02:16:30,840
 And this idea that, that some businesses have promulgated this idea that maybe consumers always want to be able to ask banks to unwind a transaction,

1640
02:16:30,840 --> 02:16:39,740
 like maybe a merchant ripped me off or, or maybe a, or maybe a, some transaction, some, some money was stolen from me in some fraudulent way.

1641
02:16:40,180 --> 02:16:44,160
 Well, not all consumers want credit or need it.

1642
02:16:44,160 --> 02:16:49,280
 And transaction finality is important to merchants who are concerned about chargebacks.

1643
02:16:49,280 --> 02:16:56,100
 So this idea that we were, we, that this is a requirement seems, seems quite strange.

1644
02:16:56,100 --> 02:17:01,480
 Um, yeah, yeah, it's almost, almost done.

1645
02:17:01,480 --> 02:17:09,660
 The, um, and, uh, I wanted to say that, that there's, that there are these questions about distributed ledgers in this that came up as well.

1646
02:17:09,660 --> 02:17:12,660
 And I want to say that distributed ledgers are not necessarily about programmability.

1647
02:17:12,660 --> 02:17:14,740
 What are distributed ledgers for?

1648
02:17:14,740 --> 02:17:23,400
 They are for creating an immutable record that can be used to, that can be used to establish the truth about whether transactions took place or not,

1649
02:17:23,400 --> 02:17:27,580
 which is, uh, what is often characterized as the double spending problem.

1650
02:17:27,580 --> 02:17:33,440
 And yes, you can use distributed ledgers to avoid certain operational costs and risks.

1651
02:17:33,440 --> 02:17:48,600
 And, uh, and you can have public's oversight of the system operators to prevent them from changing the record of history without actually having programmable assets on the ledger, without having the ledger manage tokens, without having the ledger do computations.

1652
02:17:48,600 --> 02:17:50,100
 Like these are separate kinds of problems.

1653
02:17:50,100 --> 02:17:55,700
 And there are systems like Arbitrum that have been recently proposed that actually use distributed ledgers in this way.

1654
02:17:55,700 --> 02:17:57,520
 And I think they're quite interesting.

1655
02:17:57,520 --> 02:18:07,540
 And maybe we should be looking more at those kinds of solutions rather than assume that this is going to be UTXO like Bitcoin or, or state transitions with smart contracts like Ethereum.

1656
02:18:07,540 --> 02:18:14,640
 I would suggest it's not going to be either of those, but that doesn't mean that it won't be, that it won't have a distributed system behind it.

1657
02:18:14,640 --> 02:18:20,440
 So I think that this just brings us to this question of what banks are really for, right?

1658
02:18:20,440 --> 02:18:31,920
 Uh, and taking deposits and making investments, that's absolutely banking, but payment services, which involve taking fees out of transactions, acquirer fees and scheme fees and so on.

1659
02:18:32,520 --> 02:18:40,440
 And harvesting data, you know, providing data to maybe credit or lending institutions or insurers and so on.

1660
02:18:40,440 --> 02:18:41,820
 Well, that's, that's something different.

1661
02:18:41,820 --> 02:18:43,240
 It's not banking.

1662
02:18:43,240 --> 02:18:44,120
 It's something else.

1663
02:18:44,120 --> 02:18:45,900
 And these functions can be separated.

1664
02:18:45,900 --> 02:18:57,500
 And in fact, if we look at payments as being a telecoms problem rather than a problem of banking, then we'll start to see that really the role of banks is, is historical based upon their involvement in accounts.

1665
02:18:57,500 --> 02:19:02,800
 And if we have digital currency outside of accounts, then, then the role of banks will be different.

1666
02:19:02,800 --> 02:19:08,820
 And there might even be an opportunity for other service providers to facilitate transactions who might or might not be linked to banks.

1667
02:19:08,820 --> 02:19:20,640
 And ultimately, this can be about putting control of the money for payments back in the hands of asset owners, which I think is also a concern for them, not only for privacy, but also for ownership.

1668
02:19:20,640 --> 02:19:35,680
 As parties such as the freedom convoy in Canada discovered when their bank accounts were shut off, which was effectively weaponizing this, this requirement of custodial accounts for transactions in a way that upset both the right wing and the left wing in Canada.

1669
02:19:36,880 --> 02:19:46,660
 So we wrote a paper very recently and put it out there just last week called Retail CBDC, Motivations, Opportunities, and Mistakes.

1670
02:19:46,660 --> 02:20:02,880
 And we focused on the ECB proposal and also the proposal from the Federal Reserve in the U.S. and also the Bank of England in the U.K., all of which are quite similar in many aspects of their design.

1671
02:20:03,280 --> 02:20:14,860
 So, yes, we might say that the ECB is different from, say, the U.S. because they're concerned about certain payment service networks.

1672
02:20:14,860 --> 02:20:17,380
 Well, that might be true, but yet the proposal is very similar.

1673
02:20:17,900 --> 02:20:35,300
 And I'd also want to point out that the Bank of England was advised by those payment networks and other identity providers based upon, in their system, based upon their expectations about how it would be implemented, which, again, didn't put requirements first, and therefore were in this mess.

1674
02:20:35,300 --> 02:20:37,760
 So I think we need to revisit requirements.

1675
02:20:37,760 --> 02:20:40,720
 So with that, I close.

1676
02:20:40,720 --> 02:20:42,220
 Thank you very much.

1677
02:20:42,220 --> 02:20:42,360
 Thank you.

