 And, you know, I'd like to thank Leonardo again for this invitation, because this has been a topic that I've been on the periphery of, you might say, for a long time working with the IFC and the World Bank, mostly in Asia.

1705
02:22:51,640 --> 02:23:07,460
 And Takeshi will refer a little bit more to this, where we've seen quite diverse circumstances, contexts for payment systems development and financial sector development in general, which contrast, I think, very interesting ways with what's going on here in Europe.

1706
02:23:07,640 --> 02:23:12,480
 And other countries are extremely interested in what's going on in Europe.

1707
02:23:12,480 --> 02:23:20,980
 And bridging that gap in the dialogue is something I think that we all should take an interest in, in the central banking and payment systems community.

1708
02:23:20,980 --> 02:23:29,780
 So before we get in, just, I mean, just recapping a few of the points that Jeff brought up, and I think which we want to try and explore through this panel.

1709
02:23:30,140 --> 02:23:40,700
 So I think the first thing that's on the top of everybody's mind is this issue you raised about, is doing nothing actually a choice that is reasonable?

1710
02:23:40,700 --> 02:23:54,620
 And this looks, you know, this is a very important question, I think, not just in Europe, but again, in many other markets where the speed of change in the financial system is raising this issue with a lot of policymakers.

1711
02:23:54,620 --> 02:23:58,300
 So we'll look into a little bit of that, what that means and why that's important.

1712
02:23:59,260 --> 02:24:05,160
 Obviously, we want to touch a little bit on the diverse, you know, the diverse geography of this topic.

1713
02:24:05,160 --> 02:24:14,960
 What's going on in different kinds of markets in terms of not just Asia, Europe, Africa, et cetera, but also in terms of the level and structure of the banking sector and the payment sector.

1714
02:24:14,960 --> 02:24:21,740
 And we'll get a little bit of an idea from different participants here what some of the questions are across those boundaries.

1715
02:24:23,080 --> 02:24:39,360
 Thirdly, again, Jeff brought this up in many different contexts, there are a lot of questions about market structure, which are often not really brought directly to the surface, partly because it's a very opaque market we're dealing with.

1716
02:24:39,440 --> 02:24:46,180
 I mean, most people do not get into payments sort of spontaneously because it looks so interesting from the outside.

1717
02:24:46,180 --> 02:24:52,680
 But it's once you get into the inside of it that you reveal, you know, you see that it's actually a very complex and sophisticated environment.

1718
02:24:52,680 --> 02:25:11,120
 So, but also because some of the market structure issues, I would say, are not the responsibility of the central bank per se, but they relate to a mandate that we saw kind of referred to indirectly through Evelyn's remarks about the role at a much higher level of politics.

1719
02:25:11,120 --> 02:25:15,100
 So, we'll look at that a little bit and what it means for different kinds of intermediaries.

1720
02:25:15,100 --> 02:25:37,040
 And then lastly, but not least, I think there's an interesting voyage that a lot of the participants here have kind of been on, which as we start to pull on these threads, we actually start to ask some of those fundamental questions again about the legal basis of money, its economic role and the role of the central bank.

1721
02:25:38,480 --> 02:25:48,260
 And even if we don't get just beyond, you know, we still maybe we'll get to the question of the international currency system, which also is very relevant.

1722
02:25:48,260 --> 02:25:58,100
 So, those are, I think, kind of four threads, four themes that we'll try to unpack here and bring to the audience during this session.

1723
02:25:58,100 --> 02:26:02,300
 So, without further ado, I'd like to hand over to Aniko, first of all.

1724
