 And again, like this morning, it would be very good if you could just also set a little bit of the context of where you play in this space and how you've come to it and what you're doing.

1725
02:26:11,300 --> 02:26:18,240
 And then maybe we could hear a little bit more about the experience, concretely, that you've already had in Hungary with your pilot.

1726
02:26:18,240 --> 02:26:19,420
 So, please, Aniko.

1727
02:26:19,420 --> 02:26:19,720
 Okay.

1728
02:26:20,060 --> 02:26:25,540
 So, thank you for the invitation for our Croatian colleagues.

1729
02:26:25,540 --> 02:26:33,240
 I'm Aniko Sombati, Executive Director for Digitalization and Fintech Support at the Central Bank of Hungary.

1730
02:26:33,240 --> 02:26:38,200
 And our bank is definitely not famous for doing nothing.

1731
02:26:38,200 --> 02:26:57,920
 But so, right after the launch of the Libra and Dian White Paper, Central Bank really decided to become active in searching for the future form of money.

1732
02:26:57,920 --> 02:27:19,660
 And we started this endeavor with the publication of this book, which is quite a comprehensive complement of studies for all possible angles of CBDCs, from monetary policy, financial stability, infrastructure design.

1733
02:27:19,660 --> 02:27:27,800
 And last but not least, we have a chapter on the possible design considerations.

1734
02:27:27,800 --> 02:27:39,500
 And we developed our own seven-step design framework, which starts with the question, what is the fundamental goal?

1735
02:27:39,500 --> 02:27:57,060
 Why is it necessary for the central bank to, let's say, interrupt the current setup of some kind of public and private cooperation in the payments?

1736
02:27:57,500 --> 02:28:11,760
 Is there any specific market failure that it has to solve, or is there any well-defined policy objective that would drive us into this road?

1737
02:28:11,760 --> 02:28:27,000
 And I would emphasize this question because central banks are really not about developing current, popular payment solutions for the general public.

1738
02:28:27,300 --> 02:28:35,720
 They are about, let's say, regulating, controlling, maybe influencing the market flow.

1739
02:28:35,720 --> 02:28:44,300
 But coming up with a current usable product is quite a difficult and complex endeavor.

1740
02:28:44,300 --> 02:28:58,300
 So we have been investigating the case for Hungary, whether we need a retail CBDC or a wholesale one or not right at the moment.

1741
02:28:58,300 --> 02:29:12,720
 And since we implemented a fully obligatory instant payment just before COVID in 2020, and we have a relatively developed payments market also,

1742
02:29:12,720 --> 02:29:34,140
 So we are among the few European central banks who have opened their balance sheet to the PSPs as well, so that we haven't identified any concrete reason to start implementing retail CBDC right now.

1743
02:29:34,140 --> 02:29:43,560
 But we realized that to be able for that, to build capacity, knowledge, network, we have to do something.

1744
02:29:43,560 --> 02:30:01,140
 So we first and foremost identified a youth case, which can be a small scale, but real CBDC, and which can, of course, drive us along the several steps, how to build up a working product.

1745
02:30:01,140 --> 02:30:20,580
 And this was the digital financial inclusion of young children, as Ms. Baretzi highlighted in the previous conversation, that children in the age of 8 to 14 are not really in the target area of commercial banks,

1746
02:30:20,580 --> 02:30:44,940
 But they are already tech heavy, as Mr. Cosima emphasized, they actually relied on cash, because of some legal constraints, that they are not allowed to have their own bank account and so, and last but not least, they are the potential future users of CBDC.

1747
02:30:45,580 --> 02:31:00,440
 Therefore, we started to implement our own CBDC product, which I can demo you after this, this conversation, it's called a student safe.

1748
02:31:00,440 --> 02:31:11,780
 So it's a free digital wallet for the children and of course for the parents, because legally they are liable for, for the finances of the children.

1749
02:31:11,780 --> 02:31:29,460
 And this wallet has several functions, you can top up with bank card, you can, you have different levels of KYC, depending on the deepness of your, of your transactions.

1750
02:31:29,460 --> 02:31:43,380
 You can pay by QR code, you can split the bills, you can put conditional payments, the parents even can set some tasks for the children and reward them with money.

1751
02:31:43,380 --> 02:32:03,000
 But we also have an incentive scheme, a gamification part with the crisis based on financial knowledge, digitalization, sustainability, and with the, with the correct answers, the children can gain digital coins from us.

1752
02:32:03,000 --> 02:32:15,900
 And this, they can also collect this, they can also collect, exchange, and later on redeem and at an e-commerce company so they can get physical presents for the knowledge and for the activity.

1753
02:32:15,900 --> 02:32:35,200
 And with this endeavor, we have a fully fledged CBDC, we have all the internal processes, knowledge, we actually managed to, to meet the very high security standards that the central bank sets.

1754
02:32:35,200 --> 02:32:44,100
 We have partnered actually with two Hungarian fintechs, so it was quite a cost-effective endeavor overall.

1755
02:32:44,100 --> 02:32:48,100
 And so we have a couple of thousand of users.

1756
02:32:48,100 --> 02:33:03,480
 We don't have any strong ambitions to grow, but we have this solid basis who helps us develop our system constantly and, and collect all the feedbacks, set the, the UX properly.

1757
02:33:03,480 --> 02:33:10,560
 And all, all these things, and so we are also active in the whole theorem.

1758
02:33:10,560 --> 02:33:15,980
 We have been observers to Project Dunbar together with Bank of France.

1759
02:33:15,980 --> 02:33:31,820
 We are observers in Project Enbridge, and we also participated in the tax print by the Bank of England and the BS London Center called the Project Rosalind.

1760
02:33:31,820 --> 02:33:34,580
 I think, but maybe I will talk about this later.

1761
02:33:34,580 --> 02:33:35,400
 Thank you.

1762
02:33:35,400 --> 02:33:35,400
 Thank you.

1763
02:33:35,400 --> 02:33:35,900
 Thank you.

1764
02:33:35,900 --> 02:33:36,900
 Thank you.

1765
02:33:36,900 --> 02:33:38,900
 Thank you.

1766
02:33:38,900 --> 02:33:39,900
 Thank you.

1767
02:33:39,900 --> 02:33:44,740
 Is there any, like, would you like to comment anything on what just Aniko said or shall we move further?

1768
02:33:44,740 --> 02:33:46,580
 Is there anything you would like to point out?

1769
02:33:46,580 --> 02:33:52,020
 If not, then let's please, I would just like to, Ivan, do you have something maybe pleasure?

1770
02:33:52,020 --> 02:33:54,780
 Because I would like to ask maybe Petra.

1771
02:33:54,780 --> 02:33:58,340
 Petra represents Luxembourg at the Blockhouse Technology.

1772
02:33:58,340 --> 02:34:06,760
 So we have also spotted there is this Zagreb or Croatian crew or whatever team on your, on your website, on your webpage.

1773
02:34:06,760 --> 02:34:08,260
 Could you tell us a little bit more about it?

1774
02:34:08,340 --> 02:34:15,140
 And what is your view from the industry perspective, from this technical point of view on these CBDC various projects?

1775
02:34:15,140 --> 02:34:18,980
 Because as we have found out, you have also worked on several CBDC projects.

1776
02:34:18,980 --> 02:34:21,860
 So what is your view from this perspective on that?

1777
02:34:22,780 --> 02:34:26,160
 First of all, thank you for a kind invite to join this panel.

1778
02:34:26,160 --> 02:34:29,740
 I'm, I'm very happy to be here and participate.

1779
02:34:29,740 --> 02:34:49,400
 My, my role here in the panel is a little bit different than from the other participants, because I'm coming from a commercial company, which was working on including some other projects, but the projects of developing a CBDC for emerging market countries in Asia.

1780
02:34:49,400 --> 02:35:04,600
 And mainly it was a country of Laos and in cooperation with some other partners and stakeholders, we were giving security and privacy model or considerations, uh, to be used when implementing a CBDC.

1781
02:35:04,600 --> 02:35:19,120
 Uh, what is also interesting, um, CBDCs from technical perspective, uh, posts a great challenge for anyone developing it because in terms of scalability, uh, throughput of transactions.

1782
02:35:19,400 --> 02:35:29,940
 And almost zero latency they should have as a, as a digital system, uh, it's extremely, extremely hard to build something like that.

1783
02:35:29,940 --> 02:35:45,280
 And there are also some different considerations, uh, which were, which were discussed earlier today, uh, when digital euro was explained, uh, especially with privacy, because there's always a balance between transparency and privacy.

1784
02:35:45,280 --> 02:35:55,880
 In my opinion, CBDCs are a gentle answer, uh, to emerging digital assets markets or existence of digital assets.

1785
02:35:55,880 --> 02:36:17,360
 Uh, so in some naive theory, they represent the digital counterpart of the cash and the main position of, uh, central banks, I would say to incentivize the use of such things as digital currencies is to be competitive on the market.

1786
02:36:17,360 --> 02:36:29,120
 Um, and they offer another means of currency, uh, so there is something what is legal tender, but has all of the, all of the benefits of, let's say cryptocurrency.

1787
02:36:29,120 --> 02:36:32,680
 If you'd like to have something like that and use it for payments.

1788
02:36:32,680 --> 02:36:44,160
 On the other hand, it has different benefits for emerging economies because it broadens financial inclusion, especially for unbanked or underbanked population.

1789
02:36:44,960 --> 02:36:50,720
 Um, we were working on a project, uh, which was for, uh, such, uh, such country.

1790
02:36:50,720 --> 02:37:04,640
 And, uh, the biggest benefits there was to introduce monetary stability and economic stability, because if you have CBDC, it can give you a property of greater transparency.

1791
02:37:04,640 --> 02:37:15,560
 If we're discussing wholesale CBDC and if we're discussing retail there, with the design considerations, you have to be really, really precise and cautious.

1792
02:37:15,560 --> 02:37:21,480
 What's going to happen with the, with transaction data, what's going to happen with personal data.

1793
02:37:21,480 --> 02:37:25,720
 And there's a lot of, a lot of issues around it, but I can expand it further because.

1794
02:37:25,720 --> 02:37:28,960
 What do you think, who should build that infrastructure?

1795
02:37:28,960 --> 02:37:30,160
 You said it's really complex.

1796
02:37:30,160 --> 02:37:38,000
 It's very, it's very complex and hard task to build it, to have this throughput, to have a, you know, instant payment and everything issue.

1797
02:37:38,000 --> 02:37:41,000
 Isn't it easier maybe for this public sector to build it?

1798
02:37:41,000 --> 02:37:49,620
 This is why we also sometimes think it could, it should be, but at least the backend infrastructure, the, the, the basic infrastructure, very rudimentary.

1799
02:37:49,620 --> 02:37:53,700
 And then to leave the industry to compete on, on, on all other fields.

1800
02:37:53,700 --> 02:37:59,460
 Do you think that's the good solution or, or maybe, maybe the, maybe even the, of the private sector should build it?

1801
02:37:59,460 --> 02:38:10,380
 I'd say it should be a dialogue in between, uh, public and private sector and also academia, because there's a lot of, uh, there's a lot of different roles in this system.

1802
02:38:10,380 --> 02:38:23,460
 So one is the policy maker and law, because, uh, the, the software, which will be running it or the infrastructure, which will be running it, it will be a direct representation of that policy.

1803
02:38:23,460 --> 02:38:30,640
 So CBDC will have to be compliant with certain policies and will have to serve as a promoting that policy.

1804
02:38:30,640 --> 02:38:40,640
 The other, the other thing is you need expertise because problem of CBDC can be a problem of distributed systems, can be problem of centralized system.

1805
02:38:40,640 --> 02:38:58,120
 It depends on which design option, uh, you decide, you decide to use, but, uh, it's a very interdisciplinary area, including law, including, uh, economics, including macroeconomics, because we don't know what's going to be the influence on global economy.

1806
02:38:58,120 --> 02:39:12,780
 If the speed of, uh, if the speed of transaction increases, uh, to the moment that the liquidity we have will not be comparable with the liquidity we have now, or whether our systems are going to be able to hold it even and support it.

1807
02:39:12,780 --> 02:39:18,520
 So those are all of the open questions we can, we cannot even model because we're not capable of modeling them.

1808
02:39:18,520 --> 02:39:25,020
 So designing a CBDC is an extremely, extremely tedious effort, in my opinion.

1809
02:39:27,220 --> 02:39:32,060
 That's a, I mean, building on that point, I'd like to pass over to Takeshi.

1810
02:39:32,060 --> 02:39:51,620
 Now, Takeshi, in your role, um, not just coming from Japan, but there being a key actor in the FinTech Association there, having worked with a lot of economies, um, in Southeast Asia, and also being, um, uh, a close sort of ally and, and collaborator with the central bank.

1811
02:39:51,620 --> 02:40:12,300
 And the financial services regulator in Japan, um, it'd be interesting to, you know, hear from you, to Leonardo's point, you know, if we, and, and to Petra's point, the circumstances in which we're looking at possibilities for CBDC are quite different, perhaps, in some markets in Asia.

1812
02:40:12,460 --> 02:40:23,160
 Both in terms of the existing payments landscape, but maybe also in terms of expectations about privacy or, or penetration of things like stable coins and cryptocurrency.

1813
02:40:23,160 --> 02:40:30,240
 Maybe you could outline for us a little bit what you see as the big contrasts with what we heard about the European markets this morning.

1814
02:40:30,800 --> 02:40:35,700
 Okay, yeah, so let me, uh, introduce some background in Japan, context in Japan.

1815
02:40:35,700 --> 02:40:42,020
 So, unlike some other European countries, uh, Japan, in Japan, cash is still king.

1816
02:40:42,020 --> 02:40:48,400
 So, roughly, it's 35% to 40% uh, transaction in cashless.

1817
02:40:48,400 --> 02:40:53,480
 So, that means, uh, more than 60% are, uh, paid in cash in Japan.

1818
02:40:54,020 --> 02:40:55,460
 Because, uh, there are some reasons.

1819
02:40:55,460 --> 02:41:01,360
 So, one is, uh, using or distributing and carrying cash is not expensive in Japan.

1820
02:41:01,360 --> 02:41:05,120
 So, population density is quite high and Japan is super safe.

1821
02:41:05,120 --> 02:41:12,860
