02:46:47,480 --> 02:46:49,080
 Yeah.

1878
02:46:49,080 --> 02:46:51,620
 Uh, sure.

1879
02:46:51,620 --> 02:47:00,440
 So, um, uh, sorry, I mean, sorry, I've lost my voice a bit here with a call.

1880
02:47:00,440 --> 02:47:00,800
 Yeah.

1881
02:47:03,960 --> 02:47:17,680
 Um, so, well, so, yeah, so, um, when it comes to, uh, stable coins and, uh, you know, backing arrangements are clearly a really sort of key design choice, right?

1882
02:47:17,680 --> 02:47:23,420
 and they're therefore a very key issue for stablecoin regulation.

1883
02:47:23,420 --> 02:47:31,300
 They're important because they fundamentally underpin

1884
02:47:31,300 --> 02:47:44,000
 the value of the coin and the promise of par.

1885
02:47:44,940 --> 02:47:47,160
 And this is why they've emphasized, right?

1886
02:47:47,160 --> 02:47:50,340
 So in that sense, sort of quality assets are sort of reassuring.

1887
02:47:50,340 --> 02:47:59,720
 And so, you know, you sort of want safe assets backing your coins.

1888
02:47:59,720 --> 02:48:02,680
 But, you know, I think the choice of backing assets also

1889
02:48:02,680 --> 02:48:10,420
 is going to make a difference to what sort of money, right, a stablecoin is.

1890
02:48:10,420 --> 02:48:15,900
 So I think, you know, you often hear arguments that, you know,

1891
02:48:15,900 --> 02:48:17,780
 it really is about making sure the coin is safe.

1892
02:48:17,780 --> 02:48:21,380
 And in that sense, you know, maybe you might want reserves

1893
02:48:21,380 --> 02:48:22,500
 because they're very safe and liquid.

1894
02:48:22,500 --> 02:48:26,280
 Or maybe if you can mitigate the risks associated with other backing models,

1895
02:48:26,280 --> 02:48:28,040
 then those ought to be equally good.

1896
02:48:28,920 --> 02:48:33,320
 And so, for example, I mean, actually in the UK at the moment,

1897
02:48:33,320 --> 02:48:39,540
 there are proposals that stablecoins should be fully backed with reserves,

1898
02:48:39,540 --> 02:48:42,860
 with central bank reserves, and that those be unremunerated.

1899
02:48:42,860 --> 02:48:47,560
 And there's one issue that could be for business models, right?

1900
02:48:47,620 --> 02:48:50,940
 So if you're not making any return on your assets,

1901
02:48:50,940 --> 02:48:54,220
 then what's your sort of, what's your revenue generating model?

1902
02:48:54,220 --> 02:48:57,800
 And maybe there would be, you know,

1903
02:48:57,800 --> 02:49:01,160
 maybe there would be transaction-based revenue models available.

1904
02:49:01,160 --> 02:49:03,880
 And that, you know, that's probably what we want, right?

1905
02:49:03,880 --> 02:49:07,000
 But at the same time, the potential, you know,

1906
02:49:07,000 --> 02:49:12,240
 business modifications, you know, mean that I think we see many arguing for,

1907
02:49:12,920 --> 02:49:16,100
 or maybe we should have sort of looser, you know, how to say more,

1908
02:49:16,100 --> 02:49:19,340
 we should permit a wider class of banking assets, right?

1909
02:49:19,340 --> 02:49:23,220
 So maybe you should be able to make some income.

1910
02:49:23,220 --> 02:49:28,040
 But I guess the, you know, one point is your banking assets make a difference

1911
02:49:28,040 --> 02:49:30,380
 from a sort of monetary perspective, right?

1912
02:49:30,380 --> 02:49:32,480
 So as soon as you're, if you have a full reserve,

1913
02:49:32,480 --> 02:49:34,780
 one of the interesting things about full reserve banking is,

1914
02:49:34,780 --> 02:49:39,140
 it's sort of simple in some sense in terms of the,

1915
02:49:39,140 --> 02:49:41,340
 in terms of the monetary implications,

1916
02:49:41,340 --> 02:49:44,720
 because you have a one-for-one swap of, you know,

1917
02:49:44,720 --> 02:49:47,620
 one sort of money for another.

1918
02:49:47,620 --> 02:49:51,040
 You show there's a sort of draining of reserves and deposits

1919
02:49:51,040 --> 02:49:53,920
 from the sort of banking sector by the sheet,

1920
02:49:53,920 --> 02:49:58,360
 but it's not sort of expensory in a monetary sense.

1921
02:49:58,360 --> 02:50:01,700
 Whereas as soon as you bring in,

1922
02:50:01,700 --> 02:50:07,080
 as soon as you bring in any sort of other banking arrangement,

1923
02:50:07,080 --> 02:50:09,820
 there is a sort of money creation implications, right?

1924
02:50:09,820 --> 02:50:13,980
 Because, sure, I mean, perhaps this is obvious,

1925
02:50:13,980 --> 02:50:18,300
 but it also, it often seems not to be recognized, right?

1926
02:50:18,300 --> 02:50:19,080
 In the debate.

1927
02:50:19,280 --> 02:50:28,100
 So if, if a sort of stable coin issuer gets, issue a stable coin in, in, in, in,

1928
02:50:28,100 --> 02:50:31,840
 on receipts of bank deposits, right?

1929
02:50:31,840 --> 02:50:37,500
 And then invest those in, I mean, securities, right?

1930
02:50:37,500 --> 02:50:42,240
 Then security buyer gets the deposits, you know, have the deposits and the, and the stable coin.

1931
02:50:42,380 --> 02:50:47,860
 And these are sort of both now, you know, apparently money and means of payment, right?

1932
02:50:47,860 --> 02:50:51,480
 And we, and we don't know what the, how that all works like in the wash, right?

1933
02:50:51,480 --> 02:50:54,680
 There's going to be equilibrium consequences that aren't necessarily obvious.

1934
02:50:55,340 --> 02:51:00,700
 I mean, the securities issuer might use those deposits to pay down bank loan,

1935
02:51:00,700 --> 02:51:03,980
 or it might invest them in other securities, et cetera.

1936
02:51:04,620 --> 02:51:09,220
 So I, so I don't want to sort of go into much length, but I say, you know, sure.

1937
02:51:09,220 --> 02:51:15,720
 It's about having a, a, a, a, a, a, a safe coin.

1938
02:51:15,720 --> 02:51:21,180
 And so, you know, if you had H, if you had HQA type backing,

1939
02:51:21,180 --> 02:51:24,440
 you'd want to mitigate the associated liquidity risks, run risks,

1940
02:51:24,440 --> 02:51:26,920
 but it's also about what sort of money is it.

1941
02:51:26,920 --> 02:51:30,720
 It's all, it's also has impact on business model.

1942
02:51:30,720 --> 02:51:38,720
 But then also, I think you sort of, there's the question of how this all relates to sort of,

1943
02:51:38,720 --> 02:51:40,300
 what stable coin is CBDC, right?

1944
02:51:40,300 --> 02:51:46,120
 So your backing arrangements also have implications for what the potential relationship is to CBDC.

1945
02:51:47,160 --> 02:51:52,540
 So the, I guess, a sort of full reserves, a full reserve model, you know,

1946
02:51:52,540 --> 02:51:55,540
 where you have the advantage as I described, but you're also starting to look,

1947
02:51:55,540 --> 02:52:02,640
 you're starting to get functionally, you know, much sort of closer to a CBDC in some sense, right?

1948
02:52:02,640 --> 02:52:10,340
 If you're having the full benefit of the, you know, zero credit risk,

1949
02:52:10,340 --> 02:52:13,500
 the liquidity risk of the, of the backing asset.

1950
02:52:13,820 --> 02:52:20,940
 And so then that potentially raises questions about, I mean, well, I had to say,

1951
02:52:20,940 --> 02:52:26,240
 I've not, I've not really discussed the relationship between CBDC and saying HQA back stable coin,

1952
02:52:26,240 --> 02:52:31,540
 but if you're a full reserve back stable coin, then it doesn't make sense to have both.

1953
02:52:31,540 --> 02:52:38,520
 And that's going to depend a bit on the design of the CBDC as well, right?

1954
02:52:38,520 --> 02:52:45,000
 But, um, uh, I think, I think, Jeffrey, we've had a lot, a lot to, to, to comment here.

1955
02:52:45,000 --> 02:52:48,300
 What do you think about this, if I may step in?

1956
02:52:48,300 --> 02:52:56,380
 Well, I mean, I, well, well, well, I mean, first of all, I, I, I think that the, the question about business models that you mentioned is really important, right?

1957
02:52:56,440 --> 02:53:22,320
 And, and if we look back to 2021, there was a G7, the G7 report, uh, following the summit that was held in Cornwall in, in England, uh, was particularly telling, uh, because in this G7 report, uh, it highlighted that the choice to, uh, preserve certain business models, uh, was in conflict with some potential desiderata for CBDC,

1958
02:53:22,320 --> 02:53:28,700
 such as potentially privacy or, uh, uh, uh, custody or some of these other kinds of, uh, properties.

1959
02:53:28,700 --> 02:53:37,720
 And, uh, and the question about preserving business models, since this is a political discussion at some level is, are we in the business of picking winners?

1960
02:53:38,220 --> 02:53:58,160
 Are we in the business of saying that, that there are certain businesses that we want to continue to thrive because, because, uh, I don't know, maybe they're systemically important, uh, in the too big to fail kind of way, uh, or maybe they have been involved in operating infrastructure that, uh, that has become de facto critical public infrastructure.

1961
02:53:58,160 --> 02:54:02,760
 And we need to continue to, we need to continue to, we need to continue to make sure that that infrastructure is funded.

1962
02:54:02,760 --> 02:54:06,320
 Um, these are the kinds of questions that we might need to, to ask.

1963
02:54:06,320 --> 02:54:22,140
 Concerning that last point on, on, um, uh, CBDC and, and reserve backed tokens and stable coins at the same time, I, I, I'd like to suggest that to some extent, this is a, a matter of, of, of, of, of a journey, uh, that we're on.

1964
02:54:22,140 --> 02:54:37,700
 Right. And, and, and it might be the case that jumping into CBDC right now with our particular vision for how this ought to work, uh, maybe it is financially sustainable and maybe not, maybe it preserves the public interest and maybe it doesn't, maybe people will take it up and maybe they won't.

1965
02:54:37,700 --> 02:54:53,000
 You know, these are the kinds of questions that we might not know and maybe, uh, a private sector based, uh, approach to this might be, uh, might be, uh, an efficient first step towards figuring out what CBDC eventually might need to look like or, or how that, that infrastructure needs to be built.

1966
02:54:53,000 --> 02:55:10,740
 I, I know one, one question that came up that, uh, that, um, uh, that, uh, uh, uh, Petra mentioned was the scalability, uh, issue, right? And, uh, and this question about whether scalability is, um, whether we can actually have scalability by having a highly centralized system.

1967
02:55:10,740 --> 02:55:22,880
 Well, maybe that's true. And we can also have a highly private system that's highly centralized. Like for example, the, the Torbillon work, which is highly centralized and because of its use of privacy enhancing technology, also highly private.

1968
02:55:23,000 --> 02:55:45,220
 Um, but unfortunately, uh, it has some scalability concerns because it's not operated by, um, it's operated by a central, uh, authority, which needs to run a highly available system. It needs to be a single infrastructure, which creates availability problems and risk problems. Uh, and there might be ways to, uh, to create a better architecture that has low latency.

1969
02:55:45,220 --> 02:55:58,740
 Now, I, I don't think that any system has zero latency, by the way, I, I, I, even, even digital systems, but I think we can create, we can create scalable systems this way and, and we can do it with, with some measure of, of private sector involvement and decentralization.

1970
02:55:58,740 --> 02:56:17,420
 The question is what orchestrating role does the government need to have? Operating a system isn't the same as overseeing one. Uh, and there are many examples like best execution networks where we see decentralized systems that have been properly and effectively, uh, regulated, uh, without being operated by central government authorities.

1971
02:56:17,420 --> 02:56:40,160
 So I think there are lots of questions along these, these lines that, that will come up as we go in this journey. And, and if we look at, uh, stable coins or perhaps reserve back tokens or, or some other kinds of systems like this as, as a, as part of the process of getting to a CBDC type infrastructure, then maybe we can, maybe we can, we can see what happens.

1972
02:56:40,160 --> 02:57:02,680
 We can understand better how these are going to interrelate and how they're going to play with each other in equilibrium. And, and I think that this also gets to this question about cash and CBDC and, and I, I, I can't help but, but reiterate, you know, I think if we try to make CBDC compete with cash, we're, we're not, we're, we're not solving a problem. That's a problem, right?

1973
02:57:02,680 --> 02:57:32,340
 The problem is the rise of the digital economy and reducing the role of cash. That's the problem. Uh, and if we want properties of, uh, our, um, uh, strategic properties of the CBDC infrastructure, I think that we would want to be focused on the, on the, uh, on, on the, uh, online type payments as the primary, uh, the, the primary vehicle for payments and the primary vehicle that we need to have the properties that we want simply because this is where payments de facto are going. I, I hope that helps.

1974
02:57:32,680 --> 02:57:52,960
 So I'd like, I mean, that's a, I'd like to pick up on this notion that we're, it's a journey. It's not a destination, but it's a journey. And, and your question about, are we in the business? And I, we, in the very broad sense, picking, picking winners was also question, who's, who's the one picking winners, but, um, and bring this question or set of questions to Philippe.

1975
02:57:52,960 --> 02:58:12,920
 I mean, I think that what Jeff's raising, you know, gets us to the heart of some of the legal foundations of perhaps three things I'd, I'd posit, you know, one is the, the banking system and how we legally define these different types of assets that ultimately we're talking about.

1976
02:58:12,920 --> 02:58:33,960
 But also Jeff's kind of brought the discussion one step beyond that, which is, first of all, what's the legal basis of the mandate of central banks or other authorities where, where there, there's this constant play between the objectives of preserving the stability, which sets us off maybe on one journey, but also enhancing efficiency.

1977
02:58:34,920 --> 02:58:55,920
 And secondly, the journey that is not just necessarily about the banking system, but about the financial sector, which in my language includes other species of financial institutions, notably, let's say, built on the market-based securities sector, which has different legal underpinnings.

1978
02:58:55,920 --> 02:59:02,620
 And, and maybe you could, you know, by setting the context of how you came to this debate, you know, illuminate some of those questions for us.

