2212
03:20:53,660 --> 03:20:55,920
 We have to use it.

2213
03:20:56,300 --> 03:21:05,240
 And also we know that the generally applicable citizenship-based CBDC will be the solution.

2214
03:21:05,240 --> 03:21:07,120
 But this is not the case.

2215
03:21:07,120 --> 03:21:12,900
 So CBDC doesn't have to look like those that are under proposal.

2216
03:21:12,900 --> 03:21:18,900
 CBDC, in my opinion, has to have an added value,

2217
03:21:19,060 --> 03:21:25,980
 has to have something, something extra that the market-based solution cannot serve.

2218
03:21:25,980 --> 03:21:28,520
 And what can we imagine?

2219
03:21:28,520 --> 03:21:32,740
 So, for example, in Singapore, there is Project Orhid,

2220
03:21:32,740 --> 03:21:39,860
 where they are piloting a CBDC dedicated for educational purposes.

2221
03:21:39,860 --> 03:21:43,180
 And for example, in Project Rosalind,

2222
03:21:43,180 --> 03:21:47,740
 we got into the final demo section with a use case

2223
03:21:47,740 --> 03:21:56,660
 where we used CBDC to help the government to subsidize the energy bill payments of citizens

2224
03:21:56,660 --> 03:22:03,860
 in the heightened energy crisis that we witnessed, especially last year,

2225
03:22:03,860 --> 03:22:10,400
 so that real-time targeted payment support by the government

2226
03:22:10,400 --> 03:22:14,680
 could be distributed on a DLT-based ledger

2227
03:22:14,680 --> 03:22:17,720
 with the help of wholesale CBDC,

2228
03:22:17,720 --> 03:22:25,520
 but having public policy motivation and not a general payment tool.

2229
03:22:25,520 --> 03:22:29,720
 We'll just give Basile in 25 seconds and then we'll go.

2230
03:22:29,720 --> 03:22:38,320
 So I just wanted to throw out the idea or question whether the use case for CBDC

2231
03:22:38,320 --> 03:22:42,700
 is not necessarily the policy case for CBDC, right?

2232
03:22:42,700 --> 03:22:47,240
 So, you know, is CBDC a solution-searchable problem?

2233
03:22:47,240 --> 03:22:53,020
 I mean, and as far as sort of, you know, the motivations go,

2234
03:22:53,020 --> 03:22:56,220
 different jurisdictions seem to have different motivations, right?

2235
03:22:56,220 --> 03:23:02,980
 So UK, I mean, non-UK companies sort of do dominate payments a lot,

2236
03:23:03,160 --> 03:23:06,700
 but sovereignty is not part of the debate, right?

2237
03:23:06,700 --> 03:23:12,700
 There's no sort of analog for the, you know, idea of a European payment system.

2238
03:23:12,700 --> 03:23:19,140
 The sort of policy case made for digital pound is very much focused on

2239
03:23:19,140 --> 03:23:24,240
 the importance of public money to private money, right?

2240
03:23:24,240 --> 03:23:30,800
 So we keep saying, and so, and actually top of that list is declining use of cash,

2241
03:23:30,800 --> 03:23:34,040
 but declining use of cash, well, but so what, right?

2242
03:23:34,040 --> 03:23:37,620
 I mean, so people are choosing to pay digital, why is that a problem?

2243
03:23:37,620 --> 03:23:44,040
 But, you know, the point is, or the sort of case being made, right,

2244
03:23:44,040 --> 03:23:47,420
 is the important role that public money, you know, historically,

2245
03:23:47,420 --> 03:23:53,840
 at this point in the form of cash has played in, you know,

2246
03:23:53,840 --> 03:23:57,420
 the sort of, how to say, the exchangeability, the price exchangeability,

2247
03:23:57,420 --> 03:24:04,800
 the sort of unity of private deposits in different commercial banks, right?

2248
03:24:04,800 --> 03:24:07,180
 So it sort of, you know, cash is one part of that,

2249
03:24:07,180 --> 03:24:10,820
 obviously interbank clearing in reserves is the other part of that.

2250
03:24:12,000 --> 03:24:16,580
 So if, you know, potentially, if that's the case for a sort of CBDC

2251
03:24:16,580 --> 03:24:19,220
 and public money, then the question is sort of adoption.

2252
03:24:19,220 --> 03:24:21,020
 And that's the sort of use case.

2253
03:24:21,020 --> 03:24:23,560
 If there's no use case, then you can't fix the problem.

2254
03:24:23,560 --> 03:24:27,200
 So you need the use case, that would be a good idea, right?

2255
03:24:27,200 --> 03:24:32,960
 And so it's not necessary that, you know, so, and I think, you know,

2256
03:24:32,960 --> 03:24:35,540
 that everything seems fine.

2257
03:24:35,540 --> 03:24:40,200
 So what's the, no use case, no need for CBDC, you know,

2258
03:24:40,200 --> 03:24:44,640
 partly sort of the question of looking into the future rather than where you are now,

2259
03:24:44,640 --> 03:24:48,380
 but also maybe the use case and the policy case aren't necessarily the same.

2260
03:24:48,380 --> 03:24:48,740
 Yeah.

2261
03:24:48,740 --> 03:24:50,060
 Okay.

2262
03:24:50,060 --> 03:24:55,500
 So, yeah, you'll have an opportunity if someone asks you a question.

2263
03:24:55,500 --> 03:24:56,120
 Is that okay?

2264
03:24:56,120 --> 03:24:57,680
 Please, please.

2265
03:24:57,680 --> 03:24:57,940
 No, no.

2266
03:24:57,940 --> 03:24:59,540
 Yeah, I just had one comment.

2267
03:24:59,540 --> 03:25:04,240
 So because the Japanese government is seeing CBDC or digital payments

2268
03:25:04,240 --> 03:25:08,640
 means as one use case for cross-border data transfer

2269
03:25:08,640 --> 03:25:12,600
 because all cross-border transaction payments,

2270
03:25:12,600 --> 03:25:16,280
 everything requires data transfer across the borders.

2271
03:25:17,020 --> 03:25:23,460
 So, so Japanese government is sponsoring this agenda.

2272
03:25:23,460 --> 03:25:32,760
 It's a G7 agenda and trying to arrange international global data governance.

2273
03:25:32,760 --> 03:25:39,740
 So privacy protection policies by utilizing this kind of cross-border transactions

2274
03:25:39,740 --> 03:25:42,300
 through CBDC and other payment method.

2275
03:25:43,160 --> 03:25:47,960
 Yeah, I think, I mean, that's a good point to sort of start to hand over to the audience

2276
03:25:47,960 --> 03:25:52,280
 for some questions, because I think we, we, we've, we've brought up an element we can bring

2277
03:25:52,280 --> 03:25:54,500
 to the discussion at lunch, which is use cases.

2278
03:25:54,500 --> 03:25:58,820
 I'm glad you brought up trade effectively and e-bills of lading.

2279
03:25:58,940 --> 03:26:03,480
 And that does link exactly, you know, to the problematic issues that you were raising,

2280
03:26:03,480 --> 03:26:06,580
 that the G7 is addressing around data.

2281
03:26:06,580 --> 03:26:09,980
 But I think we have, what, Leonardo, maybe 10 minutes left.

2282
03:26:09,980 --> 03:26:10,440
 Yeah, yeah.

2283
03:26:10,440 --> 03:26:11,300
 Some questions.

2284
03:26:11,300 --> 03:26:13,340
 We'd like to take questions from the audience.

2285
03:26:13,340 --> 03:26:15,100
 Please, Simon.

2286
03:26:15,100 --> 03:26:15,340
 Yeah.

2287
03:26:16,180 --> 03:26:17,200
 Thank you very much.

2288
03:26:17,200 --> 03:26:19,480
 Simon Anko, Bank of Slovenia.

2289
03:26:19,480 --> 03:26:28,380
 I really enjoyed this diversity of opinions in this panel, but I'm still of the opinion

2290
03:26:28,380 --> 03:26:32,480
 that somebody fighting for the digital euro was missing at this panel.

2291
03:26:32,480 --> 03:26:38,900
 So I will take this role, if you allow me, because there are still some facts.

2292
03:26:39,400 --> 03:26:43,220
 Everyone can have an opinion, but the facts are the facts.

2293
03:26:43,220 --> 03:26:47,660
 So first of all, I can speak for the euro area.

2294
03:26:47,660 --> 03:26:55,840
 It is very different from Bahamas, for example, or Nigeria or China, different landscapes,

2295
03:26:55,840 --> 03:27:03,040
 different political systems, different also use cases, and the legacy, of course.

2296
03:27:03,820 --> 03:27:11,260
 And I cannot agree for euro that the goal of digital euro is to reduce volume of cash.

2297
03:27:11,260 --> 03:27:12,860
 It is just the opposite.

2298
03:27:12,860 --> 03:27:22,900
 Because the volume of cash payments is declining, we want to provide society an option to pay with

2299
03:27:22,900 --> 03:27:24,360
 central bank money.

2300
03:27:24,360 --> 03:27:31,500
 And we have to be aware of typical roles or features of central bank money.

2301
03:27:32,120 --> 03:27:33,800
 It is not any money.

2302
03:27:33,800 --> 03:27:40,380
 It is obligation of the central bank, which is issuing money.

2303
03:27:40,380 --> 03:27:46,520
 So losing it, we would lose a so-called monetary anchor.

2304
03:27:46,520 --> 03:27:53,700
 For those of you who are familiar with this term, it means that it provides convertibility one-to-one

2305
03:27:53,700 --> 03:27:56,080
 every time for central bank money.

2306
03:27:56,080 --> 03:28:05,920
 If we have only commercial solutions or even crypto assets in the market, it is lost and it is important to say.

2307
03:28:05,920 --> 03:28:15,400
 Also in the EU, we have a specific use case, not only keeping central bank money available, but also fragmentation.

2308
03:28:15,600 --> 03:28:29,580
 Because we are 20 countries in the same currency area, and everyone is establishing their own instant payment solutions, Slovenia, Spain, Italy, and so on.

2309
03:28:29,940 --> 03:28:40,700
 And there is no interoperability, and with some questionable success of EPI, we need something like that also for strategic autonomy.

2310
03:28:40,700 --> 03:28:50,300
 And I have to say that maybe it's too early to decide whether we will issue digital euro.

2311
03:28:50,300 --> 03:28:54,500
 Also, it was clearly stated this morning that we have not decided yet.

2312
03:28:54,500 --> 03:28:59,760
 We may decide in autumn 25th whether to proceed.

2313
03:28:59,760 --> 03:29:04,520
 And we are not the Bahamas to implement CBDC in two months.

2314
03:29:04,520 --> 03:29:11,320
 I even know a company offering CBDC implementation in two weeks, but it is not the euro area.

2315
03:29:11,980 --> 03:29:18,020
 So, time to market is long, so we needed to start studying the topics.

2316
03:29:18,020 --> 03:29:23,900
 We have started back in October 2020 with that famous report.

2317
03:29:23,900 --> 03:29:27,100
 It is almost four years now.

2318
03:29:27,100 --> 03:29:35,540
 And what we can say at the moment, at that time, we were good in identifying questions.

2319
03:29:35,540 --> 03:29:39,640
 Today, we already have a high-level design of digital euro.

2320
03:29:40,060 --> 03:29:47,540
 So, we are proceeding, and we have also involved, as Evelyn has said this morning, market participants,

2321
03:29:47,540 --> 03:29:53,440
 50 people, experts from the market, participating in the market advisory group.

2322
03:29:53,440 --> 03:29:58,180
 So, it means that we were listening, and we are listening to the market.

2323
03:29:58,180 --> 03:30:04,880
 So, it will not be something that the NCBs without experience of UX for the mass adoption,

2324
03:30:04,880 --> 03:30:07,200
 because we have never done that before.

2325
03:30:07,360 --> 03:30:15,040
 We are aware of this, that we had never have before 350 million customers.

2326
03:30:15,640 --> 03:30:20,840
 So, we need to study all these open topics.

2327
03:30:20,840 --> 03:30:25,920
 If you read our regular reports, which we publish every quarter,

2328
03:30:25,920 --> 03:30:29,760
 these are digital euro progress reports.

2329
03:30:29,760 --> 03:30:35,260
 It is clearly written what we have achieved so far.

2330
03:30:35,700 --> 03:30:42,140
 We have never said until now that we know everything, and we have to work in parallel.

2331
03:30:42,140 --> 03:30:47,600
 We cannot wait for the parliament to adopt the regulation and then base it on it,

2332
03:30:47,600 --> 03:30:54,060
 because without studying the concepts, we would not be able to have a constructive dialogue

2333
03:30:54,060 --> 03:30:55,580
 with the commission, with the parliament.

2334
03:30:55,980 --> 03:31:02,360
 So, we have to proceed, but the end decision, even of the governing council,

2335
03:31:02,360 --> 03:31:05,020
 will not be possible without the legal basis.

2336
03:31:05,020 --> 03:31:14,700
 So, just to put some balance to the discussion of this panel, Leonardo has tried something I have added now.

2337
03:31:14,700 --> 03:31:16,300
 So, thank you.

2338
03:31:19,260 --> 03:31:28,180
 To say for the Central Bank of Bahamas, also in Italy, a person told me we are different from Bahamas.

2339
03:31:28,180 --> 03:31:29,480
 I don't think so.

2340
03:31:29,480 --> 03:31:33,460
 In the sense that every country, every experience is very important.

2341
03:31:33,460 --> 03:31:38,400
 And Bahamas now are a lab.

2342
03:31:39,160 --> 03:31:46,160
 So, it's very important to understand from what is already deployed and implemented.

2343
03:31:46,160 --> 03:31:53,920
 One other point is, especially for us as legal scholars, not any central bank is the same.

2344
03:31:53,920 --> 03:31:55,940
 It's different for the economists.

2345
03:31:55,940 --> 03:32:00,360
 But if you think, for example, of the legal framework of the European Central Bank,

2346
03:32:00,360 --> 03:32:01,520
 and you know better than me,

2347
03:32:02,320 --> 03:32:08,140
 is the unique, unique central bank in the world that is established by a treaty

2348
03:32:08,140 --> 03:32:11,020
 and not by the state or constitution.

2349
03:32:11,020 --> 03:32:15,740
 So, it's something very important, very relevant.

2350
03:32:15,740 --> 03:32:23,780
 And before, Ivan told me of the main functionality and main tasks of the central banks

2351
03:32:23,780 --> 03:32:28,460
 quoting the stability of the financial system, but the other one,

2352
03:32:29,000 --> 03:32:36,660
 and nowadays is becoming, again, a reality is the price stability, not the financial stability.

2353
03:32:36,660 --> 03:32:43,300
 And especially for the European Union, you know, the Article 1 to 7 is really relevant.

2354
03:32:43,300 --> 03:32:47,240
 Another point, 1 to 8 of the Treaty on the Function is,

2355
03:32:47,240 --> 03:32:52,100
 should be avoided to issue two different regulations,

2356
03:32:52,100 --> 03:32:55,360
 one draft for the establishment of the digital euro,

2357
03:32:55,360 --> 03:33:00,860
 and one other one, and never mentioned many times,

2358
03:33:00,860 --> 03:33:05,820
 for the legal tender of physical bank notes.

2359
03:33:05,820 --> 03:33:11,540
 So, the problem is about what a central bank does,

2360
03:33:11,540 --> 03:33:15,400
 but another point that I do not agree with you,

2361
03:33:15,400 --> 03:33:20,580
 money, the public money.

2362
03:33:21,300 --> 03:33:23,540
 There is not this distinction.

2363
03:33:23,540 --> 03:33:31,180
 Because the problem here is the power that they have the central bank to license banks,

2364
03:33:31,180 --> 03:33:35,140
 to provide for private money.

2365
03:33:35,140 --> 03:33:37,120
 But it is not money.

2366
03:33:37,120 --> 03:33:40,580
 It was clear from the slides of Geoffrey.

2367
03:33:40,580 --> 03:33:44,460
 It's the production of something that is cash.

2368
03:33:44,680 --> 03:33:47,800
 And it is misguided here, sorry.

2369
03:33:47,800 --> 03:33:52,140
 I am very, on this point, I want to be very tough.

2370
03:33:52,140 --> 03:33:59,260
 And the point is that the production of money is under the responsibility of the central banks,

2371
03:33:59,260 --> 03:34:02,800
 because it depends on what kind of licenses you do,

2372
03:34:02,800 --> 03:34:04,740
 and which is the legal framework.

2373
03:34:05,460 --> 03:34:09,720
 So, here we have a point that we do not mention, probably,

2374
03:34:09,720 --> 03:34:18,400
 but that's one of the points of the reason why we think to digital currency issued by central banks.

2375
03:34:18,400 --> 03:34:23,500
 So, when you say public money, you say something different, in my opinion,

2376
03:34:24,060 --> 03:34:27,120
 the fact that the translation in legal terms is

2377
03:34:27,120 --> 03:34:32,620
 the only one authority that has the power to issue my currencies.

2378
03:34:32,620 --> 03:34:34,220
 It's different.

2379
03:34:34,220 --> 03:34:36,440
 It's not a way to...

2380
03:34:36,440 --> 03:34:38,960
 Also, when they say, many they say,

2381
03:34:38,960 --> 03:34:41,120
 money is a public good.

2382
03:34:41,120 --> 03:34:41,580
 Where?

2383
03:34:41,580 --> 03:34:44,620
 For the economist, everyone thinks about that.

2384
03:34:44,620 --> 03:34:47,460
 If it's not a legal tender, for example,

2385
03:34:47,640 --> 03:34:49,200
 We are at the box, again.

2386
03:34:49,200 --> 03:34:51,420
 So, it's not...

2387
03:34:51,420 --> 03:34:54,820
 To put in these terms is a way to avoid,

2388
03:34:54,820 --> 03:34:58,180
 and it is especially for us, as researchers,

2389
03:34:58,180 --> 03:35:00,320
 it's important to think.

2390
03:35:00,320 --> 03:35:04,120
 Politicians have the responsibility to choose, yes.

2391
03:35:04,120 --> 03:35:06,100
 But we have to think.

2392
03:35:06,100 --> 03:35:11,140
 So, I follow up on Philippa's remarks.

2393
03:35:11,140 --> 03:35:17,260
 I think Simon made some really important statements here about motivations.

2394
03:35:17,500 --> 03:35:19,620
 real motivations for the digital euro, right?

2395
03:35:19,620 --> 03:35:24,460
 As came up earlier in Evelyn's talk as well, right?

2396
03:35:24,460 --> 03:35:31,760
 Like, some large percentage, like 70% of electronic transactions in the eurozone

2397
03:35:31,760 --> 03:35:37,360
 are taking place using infrastructure that belongs to a different country.

2398
03:35:37,360 --> 03:35:39,000
 I mean, that's a big deal.

2399
03:35:39,000 --> 03:35:41,860
 And we're talking about Visa and MasterCard here, by the way,

2400
03:35:41,860 --> 03:35:42,680
 and some others.

2401
03:35:42,680 --> 03:35:44,480
 So, let's be really clear about what it is.

2402
03:35:44,480 --> 03:35:49,220
 But there are other motivations as well.

2403
03:35:49,220 --> 03:35:51,780
 Preserving the properties of cash for the digital age, right?

2404
03:35:51,780 --> 03:35:53,020
 Like privacy, for example.

2405
03:35:53,020 --> 03:35:55,520
 And let's just say, to be clear,

2406
03:35:55,520 --> 03:35:59,340
 that a trusted third party,

2407
03:35:59,340 --> 03:36:02,620
 or assuming that we can force people to trust a specific third party,

2408
03:36:03,160 --> 03:36:07,240
 to not do something, not open the box where the data live,

2409
03:36:07,240 --> 03:36:09,880
 unless they really, really mean it,

2410
03:36:09,880 --> 03:36:15,140
 is different and is no substitute for privacy by design.

2411
03:36:15,140 --> 03:36:19,820
 And let me repeat, data protection is no substitute for privacy by design.

2412
03:36:19,820 --> 03:36:23,740
 Even though some people are asking us to accept it as a compromise,

2413
03:36:24,400 --> 03:36:30,700
 it actually isn't a compromise because it is vesting the power in the party who makes that call.

2414
03:36:30,700 --> 03:36:40,000
 So, there are definitely properties like custody and privacy and having our own control of our own infrastructure that matter.

2415
03:36:42,000 --> 03:36:46,200
 But if that's true, then why did we define, why did we design,

2416
03:36:46,200 --> 03:36:49,320
 or why is the existing digital euro proposal what it is?

2417
03:36:49,320 --> 03:36:51,620
 That's the question that I would like to ask.

2418
03:36:51,620 --> 03:36:56,060
 So, even if we can agree with the motivations, why is it what we've got?

2419
03:36:56,900 --> 03:36:59,080
 And I think it's...

2420
03:36:59,080 --> 03:37:03,220
 Yeah, I will be very sure in this reply,

2421
03:37:03,220 --> 03:37:08,260
 because I cannot explain for 20 minutes or even more.

2422
03:37:08,260 --> 03:37:12,120
 I would just say that this is the beauty of such an event,

2423
03:37:12,120 --> 03:37:13,780
 that we do not have to agree.

2424
03:37:13,780 --> 03:37:17,640
 So, this is the beauty, and I appreciate it very much.

2425
03:37:17,640 --> 03:37:21,440
 And just one last reply, and then I will pass the microphone.

2426
03:37:21,440 --> 03:37:25,820
 There is a large difference between the EU and Bahamas.

2427
03:37:26,240 --> 03:37:30,480
 In Bahamas, there was motivation behind many islands.

2428
03:37:30,480 --> 03:37:34,060
 It was impossible to pay with cash, P2P, and so on.

2429
03:37:34,060 --> 03:37:39,780
 And to my knowledge, cent dollar is packed to the USD.

2430
03:37:39,780 --> 03:37:42,760
 So, no monetary policy, and so on.

2431
03:37:42,760 --> 03:37:46,920
 Okay, sure, sure.

2432
03:37:46,920 --> 03:37:47,540
 Narrative.

2433
03:37:47,540 --> 03:37:51,260
 Also, if you think of Marshall Island, it's the narrative.

2434
03:37:51,260 --> 03:37:56,100
 I want to be a little bit short and as short as possible.

2435
03:37:56,240 --> 03:38:02,640
 So, but I have my university studies are in phenomenology, in philosophy.

2436
03:38:02,980 --> 03:38:13,440
 So, when I see this discussion, no personal thing, but it's kind of the doctors in the medieval times discussing the sex of the angels.

2437
03:38:13,440 --> 03:38:15,720
 He goes, look, guys.

2438
03:38:16,080 --> 03:38:21,280
 So, I'm the one that it is a person that pays with money.

2439
03:38:21,280 --> 03:38:21,800
 Yeah.

